[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "My Najdorf "]
[Result "*"]

{ The Najdorf has been my favorite opening since I was a child, mainly because of the games of Bobby Fischer and Gary Kasparov. There is something unique about this variation. I really like it because it is very concrete, very sharp, very correct and the list could go on and on. You can play the Najdorf all your life without a problem, you will never get bored.In 2005, when I was working with World Champion Veselin Topalov, I spent a lot of time on this opening, literally woke up and went to sleep with the Najdorf. In the last two years, the theory has changed a lot but the spirit has remained the same. I hope I can help you better understand the Najdorf and all the positions analyzed in this course. I will introduce many new ideas, but most importantly I will show you move by move how to think in these types of positions. }
1. e4 c5 { This move defines the Sicilian. } 2. Nf3
{ White has some sidelines here. The most important are:  2.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@ seeChapter 32@@EndBracket@@ andthe Alapin with  2.c3 }
2... d6 3. d4
{ The Open Sicilian. The alternatives are covered in the course, among which the main one - very important for modern theory - is  3.Bb5+  . SeeChapter 29. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ And it is this move that defines the Najdorf. The main point of 5...a6 is to protect the b5 square and at the right moment play e5. Of course the Najdorf is so flexible that sometimes we can play ...e6 or even with ...g6. This system is very rich in different plans and ideas.White has a huge amount of options after 5...a6. I will cover all of them. Usually, the most dangerous and popular ones are 6.Bg5 and 6.Be3 @@StartBracket@@or 6.f3 which is very similar@@EndBracket@@. 6.Be2 is also among the most popular ones. Then follow 6.g3, 6.Bc4, 6.g3 and 6.f4. And then many others that are very popular lately like 6.a4, 6. Rg1, 6.Bd3, 6.Nb3, 6.Qf3, 6.Qe2, 6.Qd3, 6.a3, 6.h4. White also has some rare moves like 6.Bd2, 6.Nf3 and even 6.b3. Against each move, I give options and explain my choices. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "6.Bg5 Nbd7, the rare 7.a4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5
{ The system with 6. Bg5 is definitely the most theoretical, testing, and challenging for Black in the Najdorf. There is a ton of theory and both sides should be very well prepared.It is very important for a Najdorf player to know exactly what we are doing against 6. Bg5. I recommend the system with  6...Nbd7  . I like this system mainly because it is very flexible. There is a lot of theory, but the lines are not move by move, as in the Poisoned Pawn variation  @@StartBracket@@  6...e6  7.f4  Qb6  8.Qd2  Qxb2  etc.@@EndBracket@@,  for example. Objectively, I think that 6 ... Nbd7 is not worse than the others.   The main idea of  6...Nbd7  is to play with ...e6 and ...b5 later, but also keeping the option open to play for ...e5 or even ...g6. In many lines, we can start with ...Qb6. In this sense, it is much more flexible than line  6...e6  7.f4  Nbd7  , which is also very interesting.   The main moves after  6...Nbd7  are  7.Bc4  ,  7.Qe2  and  7.f4  . I believe lately  7.Bc4  is considered to be the most dangerous for Black. I have the confidence that the lines I give are very well checked and the lines usually are very deep. The point is that I want to share with all of you the way a Najdorf player should be prepared. }
6... Nbd7
{ Instead of the main moves 7. f4, 7. Qe2 and 7. Bc4, White also has some sidelines, which we will check in detail in chapter 1. }
7. a4
{ White's best sideline on move 7. White wants to prevent b5 and then continue with Be2, O-O and possibly f4. There are some top players who have tried this move, which means it deserves serious attention. }
7... e6 8. Be2
{ The main idea of White's previous move, 7. a4. The plan is to continue with short castling.   8.a5  ,  8.Bc4  ,  8.f3  and  8.Bd3  are analyzed in chapter 1. }
8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. a5
{ This is already a good idea for White. Now,  10...b5  immediately is not possible because of  11.Nc6! }
10... Qc7
{ In the Najdorf the queen always belongs on the c7 square. Black prepares ...b5. }
11. Qd3 { Does not change much. } 11... h6 12. Bd2 b5 13. axb6 Qxb6
{ With good counterplay. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "6.Bg5 Nbd7 with 7.Qd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Qd2
{ A very standard move, but in the line with 6. Bg5 we don't see it very often at the top grandmaster level. Usually White prefers to put the queen on e2 or first play f4 and then develop the queen to f3. }
7... h6
{ Once again, including this move is a very good idea. The point is that White faces a difficult choice: to exchange the bishop or to place it on a square that is not optimal.The most standard move would be  7...e6  . }
8. Bxf6
{ Perhaps the most logical way to continue. White exchanges his bishop and wants to develop quickly and create some kind of attack with f4 or Bc4.   8.Bh4  , the most played move, can be found here. }
8... Nxf6 9. O-O-O e5
{ This is the most direct reply and also creates many concrete problems for White that need to be solved. }
10. Nb3 { Is just bad. } 10... b5 11. f3 Be7
{ White is missing his dark-squared bishop. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "6.Bg5 Nbd7 with 7.f4 and 8.Be2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. f4
{ One of the most popular moves along with  7.Bc4  and  7.Qe2  .  Now one of the ideas behind 6...Nbd7 becomes clear, as against the setup with f4 we can try to play ...e5 in one move. }
7... Qc7
{ Preparing ...e5. I believe this is very direct and also very good. White has many moves in this position. The most popular are  8.Qf3  and  8.Qe2  which we will see in the next lines. }
8. Be2
{ This move was played a lot by Grandmaster Sergei Azarov, a 1. e4 player who is usually very well prepared. The idea is to castle short and to try creating threats against Black’s king.   White's alternatives  8.Qd2  ,  8.a3  ,  8.a4  and  8.Bd3  are analyzed in chapter 3. }
8... e6 { The only move for Black. } 9. O-O Be7 10. Kh1
{ The most logical continuation. The king steps out of an eventual pin with ...Qb6. }
10... h6 11. Bh4 b5 { Now this move looks normal, as e4-e5 is not a threat. }
12. Bf3 Rb8 { Very important! This prevents all ideas connected with e4-e5. }
13. a3
{ Preventing ...b4, but giving Black important time to develop his pieces. }
13... Bb7 14. Bg3 O-O
{ Black's position is slightly better and much easier to play. A normal plan here would be ...Nb6-c4. }
