1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. f4 Qc7
{ Preparing ...e5. I believe this is very direct and also very good. White has many moves in this position. The most popular are  8.Qf3  and  8.Qe2  which we will see in the next lines. }
8. Qf3 { The most popular move after 7. f4 Qc7. } 8... h6
{ Once again I like this move. White needs to decide what to do with his bishop. }
9. Bxf6 { The only way to create some problems for Black. } 9... Nxf6 10. f5
{ The best move. Now it's not so easy for Black to play ...e6 or ...e5 anymore. }
10... Qc5
{ Clearly the best move. There have been many games from this position. } 11.
O-O-O g5
{ Black needs to somehow open the position and get his bishops into play. } 12.
fxg6 Bg4
{ The only move! Very bad is  12...fxg6?  because of  13.e5!  dxe5   @@StartBracket@@  13...Qxe5  Bc4+-  @@EndBracket@@  14.Nb3  . and White is better because of Black's weaknesses. }
13. gxf7+ Kxf7 14. Qd3 Bxd1 15. Nxd1
{ White has sacrificed an exchange for the initiative, and Black definitely needs to be very careful. }
15... Bg7 { The critical position. Now White has several options. } 16. Be2
{ Is the main alternative to the sharp  16.Qb3+  , which can be found here. }
16... e6 17. c3 { Threatening Qh3. } 17... Rhe8
{ Protecting the e6-pawn and preparing ...Kg8. } 18. Qh3 Kg8 19. Nf2 Qe5
{ Black is at least not worse. White has compensation for the exchange, but for the moment we keep everything protected.  Possibly Black can try to attack White's king by pushing b5-b4. }
