1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. f4 Qc7
{ Preparing ...e5. I believe this is very direct and also very good. White has many moves in this position. The most popular are  8.Qf3  and  8.Qe2  which we will see in the next lines. }
8. Qe2 e5
{ This is the idea behind postponing ...e6. Here Black is ready to push ...e5 in one go.   8...e6  would tranposes to another popular line in the Najdorf, namely @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.f4  Nbd7  . }
9. Nf5 { The only critical move. } 9... h6
{ It is necessary to attack the bishop. } 10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. fxe5
{ The most principled continuation. White has some other options, but in any case Black's position looks very good. }
11... dxe5 12. O-O-O
{ The critical position. Black probably has a few different ways to equalize here. }
12... h5
{ I very much like this new move. The idea behind it is to stop g4, also in some lines Black can try ...g6 followed by ...Bh6.   The main theoretical move is  12...Be6  . }
13. Ne3
{ The most natural plan. White wants to establish immediate control over the d5-square. }
13... Be6 14. Ned5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Qc6
{ Black's idea is to play ...Rd8 next or even ...O-O-O. } 16. Qe3 O-O-O
{ Now is the right moment to castle. For the purposes of the Quickstarter, we end the line here. Two White's continuations are analyzed in chapter 4,  17.Bc4  and  17.Qa7?!  - this leads to a worse position for White in view of  17...Bxd5  18.exd5  Rxd5  19.Rxd5  Qxd5  - you can find the line here. }
