1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Bc4
{ This is definitely the most dangerous move these days. I believe that 7.Bc4 is crucial for the whole 6... Nbd7 line. It is very rare that White can combine the moves Bg5 and Bc4. }
7... Qb6
{ Clearly the best move! After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Bc4  a move like  7...b5  is very much possible. But here @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1npppp/p2p1n2/6B1/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  7...b5  8.Bd5  is quite tricky for Black. }
8. O-O
{ This is not a very critical move, but it was played by some very strong players.  8.Qd2  is very attractive move, fully in the spirit of the  6. Bg5 line. Some years ago, it was considered the main line. Today, the theory has proven that Black has no problems. It can be found in chapter 6. }
8... Qc5
{ Definitely the move I prefer.   I'm not a big fan of taking the pawn with  8...Qxb2  , although after  9.Nd5  Nxd5  10.Rb1  Qc3  11.Bxd5  e6  12.Bxb7  Rb8  13.Bxc8  Rxc8  while Black's position looks very dangerous, it is quite unclear. }
9. Bd5 { The only sensible move. } 9... e6 10. Re1
{ White must continue the game aggressively. } 10... Ne5
{ The easiest way to fend off all White's threats. } 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Bb3
{ This is a safe try, but not very ambitious. } 12... h5
{ The typical move in these structures. Otherwise Black will not like White's queen landing on h5. }
13. Nce2 h4 14. h3
{ White definitely needs to block the enemy's pawn advance. } 14... Bd7 15. c3
O-O-O
{ I really prefer Black's chances. Next are ...Bh6, ...Rg8 with direct threats to White's castling. }
