1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Bc4 Qb6 8.
Bb3 e6
{ White has different plans here and he has to decide which direction to go. The most normal way to continue is  9.Qd2  and long castling. }
9. Qd2
{ The main move. As mentioned, with this move White intends to castle long. }
9... Be7 10. O-O-O Nc5 { A very critical position. } 11. f3
{ The most popular move nowadays. In the last couple of years, this line has been considered to be the most critical try against 6...Nbd7. I played it with White myself and I feel that this line is really very challenging for Black. On the other hand, if Black knows what he is doing, his chances are not worse. All the lines are very complicated and both sides can easily go wrong. }
11... Qc7 { The typical plan for Black. } 12. g4
{ 12.Kb1  It makes sense to start with this move. Most likely, however, it will lead to a transposition to the main move 12. g4.  12...b5  13.a3  @@StartBracket@@13.g4 transposes to 12.g4@@EndBracket@@  13...Rb8  14.g4  again with a transposition to 12. g4. }
12... b5
{ White has two main plans here: to play with or without a3. Personally I believe a3 at some point is necessary. }
13. a3 { The main move. The idea is Ba2 and even b4! } 13... Rb8
{ In this move order Black must play this way! } 14. Kb1
{ Another interesting move that definitely deserves our attention. You can find  14.Ba2  , the main move, starting from here. }
14... O-O
{ This is the move now. Black is ready for ...b4 push on the next move. White has many tempting options. }
15. h4
{ The most played move. Looks very logical.  15.Rhe1  and  15.Be3  are analyzed in detail in chapter 7. }
15... b4 { The best move. Black creates counterplay without losing more time. }
16. axb4 Rxb4 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nd5 exd5 19. Qxb4 dxe4
{ Black has clear compensation for the exchange, but the position remains extremely complicated. }
20. g5 Be5 21. fxe4 Bg4 { Bringing the rook to b8 with a tempo. } *

