1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e6 7. Be3 b5 8. Qd2
Nbd7 9. g4 { The main move. } 9... b4
{ The best move order.   In case of  9...h6  unpleasant for Black is  10.a3!  Bb7  11.O-O-O  This position is a tabiya with lots of theory, where I prefer White. }
10. Na4
{ The old main move. Nowadays, the other move  10.Nce2  , which we will see in the next chapter, is much more popular. }
10... h6 { It is very important to stop g5. } 11. O-O-O Ne5
{ We've arrived at the critical position of the entire 10. Na4 line.  The move 11... Ne5! was introduced by Topalov against Kramnik in Wijk aan Zee 2005, and back in 2005-2006 this position was very popular. I spent many lonely nights analyzing this position. At that time the computers were not so strong and to analyze all the crazy lines was much more difficult. Nowdays it seems that Black is doing very well without much trouble. }
12. b3
{ The main move.  12.Qxb4  is one of the critical moves that we should check, and you can find it starting from here. }
12... Bd7 13. Nb2 d5
{ Black already has fantastic counterplay. Worse is  13...Qa5?!  in view of  14.a4! }
14. Bf4
{ The most played move.   14.Bg2  ,  14.g5  ,  14.h4  and  14.Nd3  are analyzed as White's alternatives in chapter 14. }
14... Ng6
{ The best reply. Back in 2005 the most popular continuation was  14...Nxf3  15.Nxf3  Nxe4  which leads to enormous complications.   Another option is  14...Qc7  . }
15. Bg3 dxe4 16. Nc4 Nd5
{ This way Black obtains serious counterplay. The position becomes very concrete now. }
17. h4 Bc5
{ Black has an excellent game. The point is after  18.h5  to play  18...Nge7  .  The threat of ...Nc3 is very serious. }
