1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2
{ One of the most popular systems against the Najdorf, is considered to be the most positional approach.  Many great players have had this move as their main weapon against the Najdorf. }
6... e5
{ The main move.  6...e6  would lead to Scheveningen type of positions.  6...e5  is the most popular move these days, and almost all top players prefer it. }
7. Nb3
{ 7.Nf3  Since Magnus Carlsen played it, this move has become very popular. You can find it in chapter 17, starting from here. }
7... Be7
{ Practice has shown that this is the best move order. If Black starts with  7...Be6  , then White can play  8.f4  with the idea of ​​disturbing the bishop with f4-f5. }
8. Bg5 Be6
{ This is an important move that forces White to capture on f6, as otherwise ...Nbd7 will be played and Black can retake on f6 with the knight. }
9. Bxf6 { White has to take before Black can play ...Nbd7. } 9... Bxf6 10. Qd3
{ The main idea for White is to play with Qd3 and O-O-O. Clearly, this is the most ambitious plan. In the future White's plan is to push the kingside pawns with g3-f4. }
10... Be7
{ The most flexible continuation. The main alternatives are  10...O-O  and  10...Nc6  . }
11. O-O-O Nd7 12. Nd5 { Black must now exchange immediately on d5. } 12... Bxd5
13. Qxd5 Qc7
{ The most logical move, altough I believe the alternatives  13...Qb6  or even  13...O-O  with the idea after  14.Qxb7  to play  14...a5  also give Black good play. }
14. Kb1 { A very normal prophylactic move. } 14... O-O 15. Nd2
{ Another normal move. The knight on b3 is the biggest problem piece for White. The knight would like to get closer to the d5-square. }
15... Rad8 { The easiest way to stop White's plan. } 16. Nc4 Nf6
{ This is the point of Black's idea. Now ...d5 is unstoppable. } 17. Qd3 d5 18.
exd5 Rxd5 { Black has a fantastic position. } *

