[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2
{ One of the most popular systems against the Najdorf, considered to be the most positional approach.  Many great players had this move as their main weapon against the Najdorf. }
6... e5
{ The main move.  6...e6  would lead to Scheveningen type of positions.  6...e5  is the most popular move these days, and almost all top players prefer it. }
7. Nb3 Be7
{ Practice has shown that this is the best move order. If Black starts with  7...Be6  , then White can play  8.f4  with the idea of ​​disturbing the bishop with f4-f5. }
8. Be3 Be6
{ Now it is clear that after  9.O-O  O-O  we transpose to 8. O-O - see the next chapter. Here White has some other options instead of castling. }
9. Nd5
{ One of the most popular lines lately. Definitely this is very critical for the whole 6. Be2 e5 variation. }
9... Nbd7
{ Defending the b6-square and developing a piece. All the other moves are simply worse. }
10. Qd3
{ 10.Nxe7?!  is not a good idea. After  10...Qxe7  11.Bf3  O-O  12.O-O  Rac8  13.Qd2  Rfd8  Black has an excellent position. }
10... O-O 11. O-O Bxd5 { This move is practically forced. } 12. exd5
{ A very critical position for the theory. The struggle is very positional. Mostly White focuses on pushing pawns on the queenside, and Black is trying to play on the kingside. Black has plenty of different plans, though. }
12... Rc8
{ Recently, Black has more often tried  12...Ne8  . Another very popular move is  12...Nc5  , but the position after  13.Nxc5  dxc5  14.Bf3  is not my favorite. I believe White has some plus here.   Another critical option is  12...h5!?  which definitely is very interesting. }
13. c4
{ The main move.   13.a4?!  The point of Black's previous move is shown by  13...Nb6!  when White needs to exchange on b6, giving Black an excellent position.   13.Rac1  After this move, Black can already play  13...h5  ,  with a better version of 12... h5. }
13... a5
{ The old move. Nowadays more popular is Grischuk's choice  13...Ne8  . The point behind move  13...a5  is that for the moment Black wants to stop all of White's ideas on the queenside and only then start active operations in the centre or on the kingside. }
14. Kh1
{ A very normal prophylactic move. White is preparing f2-f4 and will also decide later where to place the rook from a1.White has many different ideas here. A popular plan is to prepare f4 with Rae1 or first Kh1. Another plan is to bring the rook from a1 to the center either c1 or d1 and then try to transfer the knight from b3 to b5 via d2-b1-c3.   14.Rad1  is a standard move. White supports the d5-pawn in some cases where it might be vulnerable. The lines covering it can be found starting from here. }
14... g6 { The other possible moves are  14...b6  or even  14...h5  . } 15.
Rae1 { White continues to prepare f2-f4. } 15... Re8 { A decent waiting move. }
16. a4
{ Stopping Black's ideas connected to the ...a4 advance. It also prepares the positionally desirable move g2-g4. }
16... h5
{ Black stops White's idea connected with g2-g4. As you can see, the struggle is very positional. }
17. f3 b6
{ Here Black has many different interesting plans. The position is very complicated, what I like is that Black has all his chances to fight for more than just equality. }
