[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4
{ This was Robert James Fisher's favorite weapon. It is rarely seen these days at the highest level, but it remains a very dangerous move and Black must know exactly what to do. }
6... e6
{ At this point White has many different plans. The most popular plan is to put the bishop on b3 and then start active actions with f4 or Qf3. Another popular plan is to play either 7. a3 or 7. a4, trying to place the bishop on a2. }
7. Bb3 { By some margin the main move in the position. } 7... Nbd7
{ I prefer this plan. It seems to me a bit more ambitious than Black's other moves. The main point is to immediately attack the bishop on b3 and the pawn on e4 with ...Nc5.   The other main line is  7...b5  . }
8. O-O Nc5 { White has many different ideas here. } 9. Re1 Be7 10. f4
{ The most popular continuation. However, this plan is not dangerous for Black at all. }
10... O-O 11. e5 dxe5
{ The most direct way for Black to get a very nice game. } 12. fxe5 Nxb3 13.
axb3 { Much worse is  13.exf6?  Bc5  and Black is better. } 13... Nd5
{ White already should be very careful. } 14. Ne4
{ A very logical move, but as you'll see, there's a problem. } 14... f5
{ The best defense! Black is taking over. } 15. exf6 Nxf6
{ Black is better. White's knights are unstable and the bishop pair is the most important factor. }
