[Black "6.Bc4 with 7.Bb3 and 8.f4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4
{ This was Robert James Fisher's favorite weapon. It is rarely seen these days at the highest level, but it remains a very dangerous move and Black must know exactly what to do. }
6... e6
{ At this point White has many different plans. The most popular plan is to put the bishop on b3 and then to start active actions with f4 or Qf3. Another popular plan is to play either 7. a3 or 7. a4, trying to place the bishop on a2. }
7. Bb3 { By some margin the main move in the position. } 7... Nbd7
{ I prefer this plan. It seems to me a bit more ambitious than Black's other moves. The main point is to immediately attack the bishop on b3 and the pawn on e4 with ...Nc5.   The other main line is  7...b5  . }
8. f4
{ The main theoretical move. This is definitely the most aggressive way of playing for White. }
8... Nc5 9. O-O
{ This move has always been considered the most dangerous. White sacrifice the pawn on e4 for the initiative. }
9... Ncxe4
{ I believe in taking the pawn here. it is important to take with this knight!   In case of  9...Nfxe4  White has the option to play  10.f5!  with some initiative.   9...Be7  is Black's main alternative. }
10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. f5
{ Apparently, the only way for White to keep attacking. We've arrived at the most critical line of the 6.Bc4 e6 7.Bb3 Nbd7 variation. }
11... e5 { The only move to defend the pawn. } 12. Qh5 d5 13. Re1 Qc7
{ This protects the very important e5-pawn. The alternative is  13...Bc5  14.Rxe4  Bxd4+  and here White should play  15.Kh1!  Qd7  16.Re1  Qxf5  17.Qxf5  Bxf5  18.c3  Bb6  19.Rxe5+  Be6  20.Bxd5=  with an equal endgame. }
14. Bxd5
{ Very bad is  14.Bf4?  Bd6  15.Bxd5  Nf6  when Black wins material. After  16.Rxe5+  Bxe5  17.Bxe5  Qxe5  18.Qxf7+  Kd8  Black should win. }
14... Nf6 15. Bxf7+ { White must continue the attack. } 15... Qxf7 16. Rxe5+
Be7 17. Qe2 { This pin is nasty. Black will not be able to castle. } 17... Kf8
{ The king is quite safe on f8, however. } 18. Bg5 Bd7
{ Of course, White has an attack, but it is clear that Black's position is very solid and that he has good harmony in his pieces. More in-depth analysis of this line can be found here. }
