1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4
{ A line that's been played a lot over the years, but I've always found it a bit dubious. Definitely not very popular at a high level, at least recently.   6.h4  ,  6.Nb3  and  6.Rg1  are covered in chapter 28 }
6... e5
{ Once again 6...e5. Black has many alternatives, but I do believe that this is the best move. }
7. Nf3
{ The main move. White's plan is to develop with Bd3 or Bc4 and then O-O. The other moves are even more harmless. }
7... Nbd7 { The best move order. The other line is  7...Qc7  8.Bd3  . } 8. a4
{ The main move. As usual the idea is to stop ...b5. } 8... Qc7
{ I like to prevent White from playing Bc4. } 9. Bd3
{ There is nothing better. } 9... Be7 10. O-O O-O
{ The main position of the line with 6.f4. I believe Black is completely fine. }
11. Kh1
{ Useful prophylaxis.  11.Nh4?!  is a bit dubious in view of  11...Nc5  ,  threatening ...Nfe4. Black is slightly better. }
11... Nc5 { ...Nc5 and ...Re8 are typical moves in this type of positions. }
12. Qe1
{ A very normal idea to bring the queen on the king's side. The main alternative is  12.Qe2  . }
12... Re8 { A very standard and good move. } 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Qg3
{ Threatening the pawn on e5. } 14... Be6
{ Objectively the best move. We already have seen that the pawn on e5 is not very important, and by taking it White just opens files for Black's minor pieces.   Another good move is  14...Bd8  . }
15. Qxe5 { I don't see anything better. } 15... Bd6 16. Qg5 h6 17. Qh4 Ng4
{ White should be very careful. All of Black's pieces are just fantastic. } 18.
Bd2 Rad8 { Now the rook belongs to the d file. Black has a great initiative. }
