{ White has two main options here,  9.cxd4  and  9.Bb5  . } 9. cxd4
{ Definitely the most critical. In all other lines, White risks being worse. }
9... Bb4+
{ A very important intermediate check. Worse is  9...exd4?!  10.Bb5  . } 10.
Bd2 { The only serious try. } 10... O-O
{ A very interesting novelty. Risky, but even White should know what to do.   The theoretical move is  10...Nxe4!?  11.Bxb4  Qh4+  12.g3  Nxg3  13.hxg3  Qxh1  . }
11. Bxb4 { The critical line. } 11... Nxb4 12. a3
{ Another important move that needs to be known. Other White alternatives covered in chapter 29 are  12.Qd2  and  12.dxe5 }
12... Nxe4 { A very nice shot! } 13. g3
{ Dubious is  13.axb4?!  in view of  13...Qh4+  14.g3  Nxg3  15.hxg3  Qxh1  16.d5  e4!  with a serious attack. }
13... exd4 { Both knights are hanging! } 14. fxe4 Nc6
{ A very calm move. Black has a fantastic initiative. } 15. Be2 Bh3
{ Cutting the possibility of castling. } 16. N1d2 f5
{ Opening some lines towards the opponent's king. } 17. Nc5 fxe4 18. Ncxe4 Kh8
{ Black is doing great. } *

