1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This system is known to be very solid. Many players who do not want a big theoretical battle choose this one. Personally, as a Najdorf player, I was never afraid of  4.Qxd4  . }
4... Nc6 { The most natural move. The alternative is  4...Nf6  . } 5. Bb5
{ The main idea behind 4.Qxd4. Normally White wants, after  5...Bd7  ,  to exchange on c6 and then to play either c4-Nc3 or Nc3 immediately and then Bg5 followed by O-O-O. }
5... a6
{ A rare move compared to the most popular continuation,  5...Bd7  , which is also fine. I prefer  5...a6  because is a bit more ambitious and gives Black more fighting chances. }
6. Bxc6+ bxc6
{ The bishop pair and the potentially good pawns in the center give Black hope in the long term. Of course, in the short term, Black should be careful because of the lack of development.White has many different moves, but two basic concepts. One concept is to try to attack the weak black pawns immediately, and the other is to just castle and continue with c4-Nc3. }
7. c4
{ The most standard move.  7.e5  ,  7.Qa4  and  7.O-O  are covered in chapter 30. }
7... e5 8. Qd3 Ne7 { A very flexible move. The knight wants to go to g6. } 9.
c5
{ I believe White must push c5. Without playing c5 Black has a very easy game.   9.O-O  Ng6  10.Nc3  Be7=  Black's plan is easier. }
9... Ng6 10. cxd6 Bxd6
{ I prefer to keep the queens on the board for now. The pawn structure is not the best for Black, but the bishop pair and the activity of the pieces completely compensate for it. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Rd1 { With this move White can force an endgame. } 12... Be7
{ Not  12...Bc7  13.Qc2  and Black finds it difficult to protect the c6-pawn since the usual square for queen development has been occupied by the dark-squared bishop. }
13. Qxd8 Rxd8 { The endgame looks equal. } 14. Rxd8+ Bxd8 15. Be3 a5
{ Black should wait with the development of the bishop to  e6  and make haste here with the a-pawn. After  15...Be6  16.Nc3  a5  there is  17.Na4  and there is no time to play a4; the knight will be really strong on c5. }
16. Nbd2 Be6
{ It looks pretty equal. ...a4 and ...Rb8 can be the possible ideas. } *

