{ The so-called Grand-Prix Attack. White wants to develop with Nf3, Bc4 and O-O. }
3... g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 { The most played move. } 5... Nc6 6. O-O e6 7. d3
{ White's standard plan in the closed Sicilian. } 7... Nge7 8. Qe1 O-O
{ The main position of the Grand Prix attack. The theory has proved that Black in general is doing very well. }
9. Qh4
{ 9.Bb3?!  is too slow. The simple  9...Na5  10.Be3  b6  gives Black the advantage. Tiviakov, S @@StartBracket@@2597@@EndBracket@@ - Kasparov, G @@StartBracket@@2849@@EndBracket@@, Wijk aan Zee 2001.   9.f5  gxf5!  10.Qh4  transposes to 7.Qe1. }
9... Bd7
{ Almost a new move. I think is a very good alternative to the main line. The theory goes  9...d5  10.Bb3  Nd4  . }
10. a4 { With the idea to stop ...b5 in some lines. } 10... Nd4
{ Provoking the exchange on d4. } 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Nb5 d5
{ White should be very careful. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.Nc3 d6 3.d4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 { This is the move for Najdorf Players. } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
Nc6 5. Qd2
{ This line has become very popular in the last few years. The idea is to go b3-Bb2 and O-O-O. }
5... Nf6 { The main theory goes  5...g6  6.b3  Bh6  7.f4  Nf6  8.Bb2  . } 6. b3
e6 7. Bb2 d5
{ An interesting idea. It became popular after the games of the top player Maxime Vachier-Lagrave. Black wants to create some counter-chances in the center.   Very dangerous for Black is  7...Be7  8.O-O-O  O-O  9.Kb1  . }
8. exd5 exd5 9. O-O-O Be6
{ The critical position. Black has an isolated pawn, but the activity of his pieces is very pleasant. White has some different options now. }
10. Kb1 { Logical prophylaxis. } 10... Qa5 11. Nb5
{ This was the idea of White's previous move. The endgame looks approximately equal. }
11... Qxd2 12. Rxd2 Bb4
{ A tempting move. Also very close to equal is  12...Ne4  13.Re2  O-O-O  14.f3  a6  15.Nd4  Nxd4  16.Bxd4  Bc5  17.Bxc5  Nxc5  We were following the game Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2761@@EndBracket@@ -Vachier Lagrave, M @@StartBracket@@2780@@EndBracket@@, Abidjan 2019. }
13. Rd3 { In case of  13.c3  Ba5=  The bishop on b2 is out of play for now. }
13... O-O-O
{ Black is doing well. ...Ne4, ... Bf5 or ...Rhe8 are good threats. } 14. f3
Bf5 15. Rd1 d4
{ Black should play very aggressively. This position arose in the game Engesser,J @@StartBracket@@2002@@EndBracket@@-Wachinger,N @@StartBracket@@2313@@EndBracket@@ Tegernsee 2021. }
16. Nxd4 Nd5 { Black has a lot of threats. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.d4 cxd4 3.c3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4
{ In chapter 37 we will take a look at alternatives for White to the second move, such as  2.Be2  ,  2.b4  ,  2.g3  ,  2.Na3  , and so on. In the Quickstarter we examine only the most popular,  2.d4 }
2... cxd4 3. c3 { The Morra Gambit is quite popular at the amateur level. }
3... dxc3
{ Accepting the challenge.  3...e5!?  is an interesting option, transposing to the Alapin Variation. }
4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d6
{ I personally prefer this move.  5...e6  is another very decent plan. } 6. Bc4
{ The best square for the bishop. } 6... a6
{ I think is similar to the more usual  6...e6  ,  but maybe a bit more precise. It stops Nb5 in some lines and also prepares b7-b5 in the future. }
7. O-O Nf6 8. Bf4 e6 { The most logical move. Another option is  8...Bg4  . }
9. Qe2 Be7
{ The simplest way to develop. Another option is to include  9...Nh5  first. }
10. Rfd1 { White is already threatening e4-e5. } 10... Qc7 11. Rac1 O-O 12. h3
Nd7
{ Of course Black has many other good moves. The plan now is to transfer the knight to e5. }
13. Bb3 Qb8
{ The position is still complicated, but Black is for sure at least not worse. More in-depth analysis of this line can be found here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 6.Bg5 Nbd7 Rare Lines"]
[Black "6.Bg5 Nbd7 Rare Lines: 7.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5
{ The system with 6. Bg5 is definitely the most theoretical, testing, and challenging for Black in the Najdorf. There is a ton of theory and both sides should be very well prepared.It is very important for a Najdorf player to know exactly what we are doing against 6. Bg5. I recommend the system with  6...Nbd7  . I like this system mainly because it is very flexible. There is a lot of theory, but the lines are not move by move, as in the Poisoned Pawn variation  @@StartBracket@@  6...e6  7.f4  Qb6  8.Qd2  Qxb2  etc.@@EndBracket@@,  for example. Objectively, I think that 6 ... Nbd7 is not worse than the others.   The main idea of  6...Nbd7  is to play with ...e6 and ...b5 later, but also keeping the option open to play for ...e5 or even ...g6. In many lines, we can start with ...Qb6. In this sense, it is much more flexible than line  6...e6  7.f4  Nbd7  , which is also very interesting.   The main moves after  6...Nbd7  are  7.Bc4  ,  7.Qe2  and  7.f4  . I believe lately  7.Bc4  is considered to be the most dangerous for Black. I have the confidence that the lines I give are very well checked and the lines usually are very deep. The point is that I want to share with all of you the way a Najdorf player should be prepared. }
6... Nbd7
{ Instead of the main moves 7. f4, 7. Qe2 and 7. Bc4, White also has some sidelines, which we will check in this chapter. }
7. g3
{ This move seems a bit awkward. Usually White wants to castle long and push f4 and g4. }
7... h6
{ It is very important to include this move. The point is that White does not have a good square for his bishop. }
8. Bxf6 { Exchanging the bishop is not a very good idea here. } 8... Nxf6 9.
Bg2 e5 10. Nb3 Be7 { With the bishop pair Black is already better. } *

