1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5
{ The system with 6. Bg5 is definitely the most theoretical, testing, and challenging for Black in the Najdorf. There is a ton of theory and both sides should be very well prepared.It is very important for a Najdorf player to know exactly what we are doing against 6. Bg5. I recommend the system with  6...Nbd7  . I like this system mainly because it is very flexible. There is a lot of theory, but the lines are not move by move, as in the Poisoned Pawn variation  @@StartBracket@@  6...e6  7.f4  Qb6  8.Qd2  Qxb2  etc.@@EndBracket@@,  for example. Objectively, I think that 6 ... Nbd7 is not worse than the others.   The main idea of  6...Nbd7  is to play with ...e6 and ...b5 later, but also keeping the option open to play for ...e5 or even ...g6. In many lines, we can start with ...Qb6. In this sense, it is much more flexible than line  6...e6  7.f4  Nbd7  , which is also very interesting.   The main moves after  6...Nbd7  are  7.Bc4  ,  7.Qe2  and  7.f4  . I believe lately  7.Bc4  is considered to be the most dangerous for Black. I have the confidence that the lines I give are very well checked and the lines usually are very deep. The point is that I want to share with all of you the way a Najdorf player should be prepared. }
6... Nbd7
{ Instead of the main moves 7. f4, 7. Qe2 and 7. Bc4, White also has some sidelines, which we will check in this chapter. }
7. g3
{ This move seems a bit awkward. Usually White wants to castle long and push f4 and g4. }
7... h6
{ It is very important to include this move. The point is that White does not have a good square for his bishop. }
8. Be3 e6 9. Bg2 Qc7
{ Black should start with this move now, as  9...b5  is not possible in view of  10.e5  . }
10. O-O Be7 11. f4 Nb6
{ The knight aims at the square c4. I believe Black has very good counterplay. }
12. Kh1 Nc4 13. Bc1 Bd7 { Simply developing. ...Rc8 will come next. } 14. b3
Na5 15. Bb2 Nc6
{ Black has a very comfortable position. The next moves are ...O-O and ...Rc8. }
