[White "2) 6.Bg5 Nbd7 7.Qd2 "]
[Black "7.Qd2 with 8.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Qd2
{ A very standard move, but in the line with 6. Bg5 we don't see it very often at the top grandmaster level. Usually White prefers to put the queen on e2 or first play f4 and then develop the queen to f3. }
7... h6
{ Once again, including this move is a very good idea. The point is that White faces a difficult choice: to exchange the bishop or to place it on a square that is not optimal.The most standard move would be  7...e6  . }
8. Be3 { An alternative move. } 8... e6 9. f3 b5
{ We are entering a theoretical position with an extra tempo for Black. In this particular position, ...h6 is very useful, because in many lines when White pushes g4, Black would play ...h6 anyway. }
*

