1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Qd2
{ A very standard move, but in the line with 6. Bg5 we don't see it very often at the top grandmaster level. Usually White prefers to put the queen on e2 or first play f4 and then develop the queen to f3. }
7... h6
{ Once again, including this move is a very good idea. The point is that White faces a difficult choice: to exchange the bishop or to place it on a square that is not optimal.The most standard move would be  7...e6  . }
8. Bxf6
{ Perhaps the most logical way to continue. White exchanges his bishop and wants to develop quickly and create some kind of attack with f4 or Bc4. }
8... Nxf6 9. f4 e5
{ A very good answer to White's 9. f4.This is a very typical push in this line. This is one of the points of 6...Nbd7: we didn't yet commit to ...e6, and in some variations we can play ...e5 in one move instead. }
10. Nf5
{ Tempting, but Black now has many different ways to gain a good position.  10.Nf3  Qc7  11.O-O-O  Be7  I prefer Black here because of the bishop pair. }
10... Nxe4
{ The most direct way. I believe Black has some alternatives as well. } 11.
Nxg7+ Bxg7 12. Nxe4 O-O
{ With the bishop pair Black has an excellent position. } *

