1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. f4
{ One of the most popular moves along with  7.Bc4  and  7.Qe2  .  Now one of the ideas behind 6...Nbd7 becomes clear, as against the setup with f4 we can try to play ...e5 in one move. }
7... Qc7
{ Preparing ...e5. I believe this is very direct and also very good. White has many moves in this position. The most popular are  8.Qf3  and  8.Qe2  which we will see in the next chapters. }
8. Qd2
{ The queen's place is on f3 or e2. Now Black gets a very good version of the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.f4  Nbd7  . }
8... e6 9. O-O-O b5
{ With the queen on e2 or f3, the position is very double-edged. Now Black's play is easier. }
10. a3 { For the moment stopping ...b4. } 10... Bb7 11. Bd3 Be7
{ Black is already perfectly fine. White's pieces are not optimally placed. }
12. g4 O-O 13. f5 Nc5 { Black is at least slightly better. } *

