[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. f4
{ One of the most popular moves along with  7.Bc4  and  7.Qe2  .  Now one of the ideas behind 6...Nbd7 becomes clear, as against the setup with f4 we can try to play ...e5 in one move. }
7... Qc7
{ Preparing ...e5. I believe this is very direct and also very good. White has many moves in this position. The most popular are  8.Qf3  and  8.Qe2  which we will see in the next chapters. }
8. Bd3 h6 { The usual way to proceed. } 9. Bh4
{ It looks normal to keep the bishop. } 9... g5 { Opening some files. } 10.
fxg5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Qb6
{ Black can now take advantage of the fact that the bishop is on d3 by attacking both the pawn on b2 and the knight on d4. Now, for example,  12.Nb3?  is a mistake because of  12...Rxh2!  with a very big advantage for Black. }
