1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Qe2
{ One of the most dangerous moves. In this line, Black need to know a lot, but what I like about the whole 6... Nbd7 line is that Black also has a good chance of playing for a win. There are not many forced draws. In this line, in order to fight for an advantage, White must take risks. }
7... h6
{ One of the most principled continuations. The other option is  7...e6  8.f4  Qc7  which transposes to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.f4  Nbd7  . }
8. Bd2 { A possible move, but Black doesn't seem to have any problems. } 8...
g6
{ With the bishop on d2, this plan seems very logical. Now that square e3 is available, it is better not to allow the knight the maneuver Nf5-e3. }
9. f4 e5
{ Now it is important to break in the center. If we leave White the option of playing e5, we end up in a difficult position. }
10. Nb3 { 10.fxe5  Nxe5  11.O-O-O  Bg7⩱  and Black has a very good position. }
10... b5 { Clearly, Black is doing well. } 11. a3
{ Stopping ...b4. But now Black can play on the c4-square. } 11... Nb6
{ The threat of ...Nc4 is very strong. } *

