{ One of the most principled continuations. The other option is  7...e6  8.f4  Qc7  which transposes to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.f4  Nbd7  . }
8. Bh4
{ Clearly the critical move. For now White wants to keep his bishop in the game. }
8... g6
{ The point of Black's previous move. Black definitely wants to meet f4 with ....e5! }
9. f4
{ This is the critical move. The whole line is very double-edged. Both sides should be very well prepared. }
9... e5 { The usual response to f2-f4. } 10. Nf3
{ This does not create big problems for Black. } 10... Qc7 11. O-O-O b5
{ Black has placed all his pieces well. The next moves will be ...Bb7 and then either ...Bg7 or ...Be7, depending on what White does. }
12. g3 { A normal move. The idea is clearly to play Bh3. } 12... Bg7 13. Bh3
{ After  13.Qd3  b4  White is just worse. After ...Bb7 White will have problems with the pawn on e4. }
13... Bb7 { Black is very quick to create counterplay. } 14. a3
{ This prevents ... b4, but gives Black an important tempo. } 14... exf4 15.
gxf4 O-O
{ Black is better. ...Rfe8 is coming next, with the idea to put pressure on the e4-pawn. }
