9... e5 { The usual response to f2-f4. } 10. fxe5 dxe5 11. O-O-O
{ The most critical line. } 11... Qc7
{ Now  11...exd4?  is very bad in view of  12.e5  and White wins. } 12. Nb3
{ The other move are worse, for example  12.Nf3  b5  and Black gets very good counterplay. }
12... b5
{ We've arrived at the critical position for the whole 7. Qe2 line. White has many different options here. According to my analysis, though, Black should be fine. }
13. Qf3 { A very critical line. Black must know exactly what to do here. }
13... Bg7
{ Now the bishop comes to g7.   If  13...Be7?  White wins after  14.Rxd7! } 14.
a3 O-O 15. Kb1 Bb7 16. g4 Rab8 { The only good plan for Black. } 17. Bd3 Ba8
{ Preparing ...a5 and then ...b4. } 18. g5 hxg5 19. Bxg5 a5
{ Once again it is very important to start with this move instead of the direct ...b4. }
20. Nxb5 { The critical line. } 20... Qc6
{ The only way for Black to continue. } 21. a4 Nxe4
{ The next couple of moves are very forced. } 22. Qxe4 Qxe4 23. Bxe4 Bxe4 24.
Rhe1 Bf5 { Just in time to protect all pieces. } 25. Nd6
{ Just bad is  25.Nxa5?!  in view of  25...Rfc8  .  The pawn on c2 is a big problem for White. }
25... Bg4
{ The endgame is very sharp. The bishop pair gives Black very good possibilities, though. }
*

