{ Clearly the best move! After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  6...e6  7.Bc4  a move like  7...b5  is very much possible. But here @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1p1npppp/p2p1n2/6B1/2BNP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QK2R b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  7...b5  8.Bd5  is quite tricky for Black. }
8. Qd2
{ A very attractive move, fully in the spirit of the 6.Bg5 line. Some years ago, it was considered the main line. Today, theory has proven that Black has no problems. }
8... Qxb2
{ Black has no choice but to accept the challenge.  8...Qc5  is our choice when White continues with 8.O-O, but here it doesn't work; the queen already defends the bishop on g5, and White can play  9.Bb3  retaining the option of castling long. }
9. O-O { Another critical move. } 9... Qb4
{ I believe this is the best answer. } 10. Bb3 e6 11. Rad1
{ The only move that keeps White in the game. } 11... Be7 12. Bxe6
{ White is ready now for this sacrifice. This is the only way to create some attacking chances. }
12... fxe6 13. Nxe6 Kf7
{ The only way to defend the pawn on g7 and escape from the threat of Nc7+. }
14. Nc7 Nb6
{ The only defense! The point is that after  14...Rb8  White can continue with  15.N7d5  , attacking the queen; and after  15...Qc5  16.Nxe7  Kxe7  17.e5  , opening up the centre, Black's king position is very dangerous. }
15. Rb1 { An important intermediate move. } 15... Qc5
{ The next few moves are forced. } 16. Nxa8 Nxa8 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nd5 Nc7
{ The knight is coming back into the game. } 19. Nxf6 gxf6 20. Rfd1
{ The best move. The chances are approximately equal. } 20... Re8
{ One of the good moves here. } 21. Qh6 Rg8 { A strange but necessary move. }
22. Qxh7+ Rg7 23. Qh6 Ne6 { Very soon Black will activate his pieces. } *

