[White "7) 6.Bg5 Nbd7 7.Bc4 with 8.Bb3"]
[Black "6.Bg5 Nbd7 7.Bc4 with 8.Bb3 and 9.a4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Bc4 Qb6 8.
Bb3 e6
{ White has different plans here and he has to decide which direction to go. The most normal way to continue is  9.Qd2  and long castling. }
9. a4
{ A slightly strange move in combination with White's previous moves. The idea is that after a5 the black queen will not have a good place to go. }
9... Qa5 { Practically forced. Black cannot allow White to play a5. } 10. Qd2
h6
{ I believe it is important to include this move. In practice this provokes the exchange of the bishop. }
11. Bxf6
{ 11.Bh4?!  A dubious move.  11...Be7  The Ne4 threat is quite unpleasant.   11.Be3  is possible but it looks a little awkward because of  11...Ng4!  It is always good to exchange this bishop. }
11... Nxf6 12. f4 Nd7
{ This is a necessary move. The knight must reach c5 as quickly as possible. }
13. O-O { An alternative to the direct  13.f5  . } 13... Nc5 14. Ba2 Bd7 15. f5
{ This position seems very unclear. I prefer Black because the dark-squared bishop is potentially strong. }
15... O-O-O { The move I prefer. } 16. Nf3 Kb8 { A very useful move. } 17. Qd4
{ Threatening b4. } 17... Nxa4
{ With this move Black will manage to equalize by force. } 18. Nxa4
{ After  18.Bb3  Nxc3!  19.Rxa5  Ne2+  20.Kh1  Nxd4  21.Nxd4  d5!  Black is better. }
18... Qxa4 19. Qxa4 Bxa4 20. fxe6 fxe6 21. Nd4
{ White seems to be doing well, but Black has a strong continuation. } 21... d5
22. Nxe6 dxe4 { Black must sacrifice the exchange. } 23. Bc4
{ This is a good inclusion for White. } 23... Bc6 24. Nxd8 Bc5+ 25. Kh1 Rxd8
{ It is clear that Black has enough compensation for the exchange. } *

