1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3
{ This is definitely one of the most dangerous systems against the Najdorf. The so-called English Attack is related to the plan f3-Qd2 and O-O-O. White can also start with  6.f3  , which makes a lot of difference for us. Against  6.Be3  I suggest  6...Ng4  which was Garry Kasparov's favourite.   I think that theory has nothing against  6...Ng4  . Black is perfectly fine and there is no reason to play anything else. The only problem I find is that White can repeat moves with  7.Bc1  ,  but this should not be the reason for not playing 6...Ng4. Instead of repeating moves, I will give an alternative after 7.Bc1,  and that is to play  7...Nc6  , which can work very well in some circumstances. }
6... Ng4
{ Kasparov's pet move. In the last years this has been played a lot by the top grandmaster Vachier-Lagrave. It's one of the most popular systems against 6. Be3. }
7. Bg5 h6 8. Bc1
{ A modern way to escape the main line of  8.Bh4  .   8.Bd2?!  does not make any sense. After  8...Qb6!  9.f3  Qxd4  10.fxg4  Be6  Black is better. }
8... Nf6 9. Bc4 { This is the most played move by far. } 9... e6 10. Bb3
{ White hopes to make some use of the fact that the pawn is on h6. } 10... Nbd7
{ I still like this plan. Probably Black can play also with  10...b5  . } 11.
f4 Nc5 12. e5
{ This is the only way to use the fact that Black has played ...h6. } 12...
Nfd7 13. Nxe6
{ White must act quickly.   If  13.exd6?!  , then  13...Nf6!  looks good for Black. }
13... Nxe6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Qh5+ Ke7 16. Be3
{ It is clear that White has an attack, but on the other hand Black should be able to defend succesfully. }
16... dxe5 17. O-O-O { Also a draw is  17.Qh4+  Ke8  18.Qh5+  Ke7= } 17... Qe8
{ Now White must take the draw. } 18. Rxd7+ Bxd7 19. Bc5+ Kd8 20. Bb6+ Ke7
{ With a draw. } *

