[White "8) 6.Be3 Ng4 Rare Lines "]
[Black "6.Be3 Ng4 Rare Lines: 7.Bg5 h6 8.Bc1 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3
{ This is definitely one of the most dangerous systems against the Najdorf. The so-called English Attack is related to the plan f3-Qd2 and O-O-O. White can also start with  6.f3  , which makes a lot of difference for us. Against  6.Be3  I suggest  6...Ng4  which was Garry Kasparov's favourite.   I think that theory has nothing against  6...Ng4  . Black is perfectly fine and there is no reason to play anything else. The only problem I find is that White can repeat moves with  7.Bc1  ,  but this should not be the reason for not playing 6...Ng4. Instead of repeating moves, I will give an alternative after 7.Bc1,  and that is to play  7...Nc6  , which can work very well in some circumstances. }
6... Ng4
{ Kasparov's pet move. In the last years this has been played a lot by the top grandmaster Vachier-Lagrave. It's one of the most popular systems against 6. Be3. }
7. Bg5 h6 8. Bc1
{ A modern way to escape the main line of  8.Bh4  .   8.Bd2?!  does not make any sense. After  8...Qb6!  9.f3  Qxd4  10.fxg4  Be6  Black is better. }
8... Nf6 9. Bd3
{ The modern move, which is very similar to the variation 6. Bd3. With the pawn on h6 in many lines Black cannot play with ...g6. Moves like  9.g3  ,  9.Be2  ,  9.a4  and  9.Be3  do not make much sense, since after  9...e5  having the pawn on h6 for free will be clearly in Black's favour. }
9... e5
{ Black has many options here. For me 9... e5 feels like the best move. } 10.
Nde2
{ 10.Nb3  It does not make sense to go there. After  10...Be7  it is not clear why the pawon on h6 is bad here. }
10... Be7 11. O-O Nbd7
{ I prefer this plan, because it is more flexible. The knight goes to c5. } 12.
Ng3 Nc5 13. Be2 { It makes sense to keep the bishop. } 13... g6
{ I like this move a lot. The next move h5 looks quite logical with the knight on g3. }
14. f4
{ The main plan for White.   Also a standard move is  14.Be3  . Now Black has time to play  14...h5!  Pushing ...h4 can be very unpleasant for White. }
14... h5 { Black continues with his plan. } 15. fxe5
{ White must go for the endgame. ...h4 is a very unpleasant threat. } 15...
dxe5 16. Qxd8+ Bxd8 17. Bg5 Ncd7
{ Black has at least equal chances in the endgame. The threats of ...Bb6+ and ...h5-h4 are quite serious. }
*

