g5 9. Bg3 Bg7
{ We've arrived at the main position of the 6... Ng4 line. Now White has many different options. The latest theory suggests that there are only a few moves that can create some problems for Black. }
10. Qd2
{ Quite a popular move. The idea is after  10...Nc6  to play  11.Nb3  . } 10...
Nc6 { The only logical move. } 11. Nf5 { This line looks good for Black. }
11... Bxf5 12. exf5 Qb6 13. Rb1
{ After  13.Na4  Qd4  14.Qxd4  Bxd4  15.Be2  Nf6  Black has the better chances. The bishop on g3 is completely out of the game.   13.O-O-O  Rc8  is very dangerous for White. }
13... Qc5 14. Bd3 Nge5 15. Be4 Rd8
{ Black controls very important squares, threatens ...Nc4, and in some lines prepares d6-d5.   For example after  16.Bxe5  Qxe5  17.O-O  very strong is  17...d5!  This is the reason why 15...Rd8 instead of ...Rc8.  18.Bxd5?!  Now this is much worse for White after  18...Nb4  19.Rbd1  Qc7!  Threatening ...Bxc3.  20.Nb5  Still not easy, but Black is much better after  20...Qf4!  21.Qxb4  Qxb4  22.Bc6+  A nice idea. The point is that 22...bxc6 leads to checkmate after 23.Nc7+ and Rxd8 next.  22...Rd7!  23.Nc7+  Kf8  24.Rxd7  Be5  Black has a great chance of winning the game. }
