{ Maybe Black has also other moves like  15...Qb6  ,  15...Qc7  or even  15...d5  followed by  16.b3  Bb5  . }
16. Na3 Qc8 17. c3 Nd7
{ Black's position is very solid. The minor pieces are very nicely placed. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) 6.Be3 Ng4 with 10.Be2 "]
[Black "6.Be3 Ng4 with 10.Be2 #18"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 Ng4 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4
g5 9. Bg3 Bg7 10. Be2
{ This is the old main move of this variation. For many years, this was the most popular way to play. Nowadays, the main move is 10. h3, which we will discuss in the next chapter. }
10... h5 11. Bxg4 { The main move. } 11... Bxg4
{ This move has not been very popular in recent years. Many years ago it was the main choice of Garry Kasparov. I believe that it's much easier than  11...hxg4  . Without having to know too much theory Black will get at least equal chances.   11...hxg4  is currently the most popular move. Theory suggests that Black equalizes in this line as well. The only problem is that there is a lot of theory and Black has to remember a lot of forced lines. }
12. f3 h4
{ A very rare move. It has never been played by strong players.  12...Bd7  is the main move. }
13. Bf2 Be6
{ This position is quite new. I believe that Black is absolutely fine and has his chances. }
14. h3 { Probably the critical move. It stops ...h3. } 14... Bc4
{ A very difficult move to make. The point is that for now, it prevents White from castling. Now different is  14...Nc6  15.O-O  Nxd4  16.Bxd4  Be5  17.Nd5  Rc8  18.c3  f6  19.Kh1  when White is slightly better. For Black, it is difficult to gain any counterplay here. }
15. b3
{ The most natural response. Another logical continuation is  15.Qd2  Qa5!  when play likely transposes to the main line after  16.b3  . }
15... Qa5 { The whole point of Black's previous move was to provoke b3. } 16.
Qd2 Be6 17. O-O { This is not dangerous for Black at all. } 17... Nc6 18. Rad1
Rc8
{ Looks very simple for Black. Now we are even threatening ... Nxd4 winning a piece. }
*

