{ The knight will come to f4 via h5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 6.Be3 Ng4 with 10.h3"]
[Black "6.Be3 Ng4 with 10.h3 & 11.Qe2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 Ng4 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4
g5 9. Bg3 Bg7 10. h3 Nf6
{ A less popular move, although played by some great players such as Kasparov, Carlsen, Karjakin, Giri and many others. It has less theory than  10...Ne5  , but I think Black definitely has his chances, although he obviously needs to know some concrete lines. The main idea of  10...Nf6  is that it puts some pressure on the e4-pawn. White has many different options, the most popular being  11.Qf3  ,  11.Bc4  ,  11.Be2  and  11.Qe2  .   The main theoretical move is  10...Ne5  when both  11.Nf5  and  11.f3  are very critical. }
11. Qe2 { Definitely a very interesting try. This is similar to  11.Qf3  . }
11... Nc6 { Black must start with this move. } 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. e5
{ The point behind 11. Qe2. } 13... dxe5 14. Bxe5 O-O
{ The critical position. } 15. g3
{ The most natural move. White simply wants to develop his pieces. } 15... a5
{ The best move. The ideas are ...Ba6 and also ...a4 to continue with ...Ra5. }
16. Bg2 a4
{ The main difference with White playing g4 and h4 instead of g3 and Bg2 is that Black now has some ideas connected to ...Ng4, as we are about to see. }
17. Qe3 Ra5 { ...Ng4 is now a serious threat. } 18. Bd4
{ This is obviously bad, as White is about to lose the bishop. } 18... Ng4
{ Black wins. } *

