[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 Ng4 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4
g5 9. Bg3 Bg7 10. h3 Nf6
{ A less popular move, although played by some great players such as Kasparov, Carlsen, Karjakin, Giri and many others. It has less theory than  10...Ne5  , but I think Black definitely has his chances, although he obviously needs to know some concrete lines. The main idea of  10...Nf6  is that it puts some pressure on the e4-pawn. White has many different options, the most popular being  11.Qf3  ,  11.Bc4  ,  11.Be2  and  11.Qe2  .   The main theoretical move is  10...Ne5  when both  11.Nf5  and  11.f3  are very critical. }
11. Bc4
{ One of the most dangerous moves for Black, introduced by Garry Kasparov in his game against Judit Polgar in Wijk aan Zee, 2000. }
11... b5
{ A rare move. In my opinion with accurate play Black can equalize with 11... b5.   The main move is  11...Qb6  . }
12. Bb3 b4 13. Nd5
{ The most natural reply.   Black should be fine after  13.Na4  O-O  14.Qd3  Qa5  when ...Bd7 is an unpleasant threat. }
13... Nxe4 { The line now becomes very forcing. } 14. Qf3
{ The only reasonable way to continue. } 14... Nxg3 15. Nc7+
{ As mentioned, the next couple of moves are very forced. } 15... Qxc7 16.
Qxf7+ Kd8 17. Qxg7 Re8 { The only safe place for the rook. } 18. fxg3 e5
{ The whole point. White is forced to exchange the queens. } 19. Nf5 Qxg7 20.
Nxg7 Re7 21. Nh5 Bb7
{ ...Bb7 in combination with ...Nd7 is the most normal way to place our pieces. }
22. O-O Nd7 23. Rad1 Kc7
{ The endgame is approximately equal. Black's next move can be ...a5. } *

