g5 9. Bg3 Bg7 10. h3 Nf6
{ A less popular move, although played by some great players such as Kasparov, Carlsen, Karjakin, Giri and many others. It has less theory than  10...Ne5  , but I think Black definitely has his chances, although he obviously needs to know some concrete lines. The main idea of  10...Nf6  is that it puts some pressure on the e4-pawn. White has many different options, the most popular being  11.Qf3  ,  11.Bc4  ,  11.Be2  and  11.Qe2  .   The main theoretical move is  10...Ne5  when both  11.Nf5  and  11.f3  are very critical. }
11. Be2 { A very normal developing move. } 11... O-O
{ This natural move is almost new. } 12. Qd2 { The most critical. } 12... b5
13. a3 { White must stop b4. } 13... e5
{ A necessary move, leading to very big complications. } 14. Nb3 Be6 15. O-O-O
Nc6 { Black must play vigorously. } 16. Qxd6 Qc8
{ This is the whole point. White has problems with his queen. } 17. Nd5
{ The most critical line. } 17... Ra7
{ Stopping the trick Qxc6 followed by Ne7+. } 18. Bf3
{ Another critical option. } 18... Rd8
{ Still playing on the theme of the awkward position of White's queen. } 19.
Qc5 Nxd5 20. exd5 Na5 { The only way! } 21. Qxc8 Nxb3+ 22. cxb3 Rxc8+ 23. Kd2
Bd7 { Black has very good compensation for the pawn. } *

