[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 Ng4 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4
g5 9. Bg3 Bg7 10. h3 Nf6
{ A less popular move, although played by some great players such as Kasparov, Carlsen, Karjakin, Giri and many others. It has less theory than  10...Ne5  , but I think Black definitely has his chances, although he obviously needs to know some concrete lines. The main idea of  10...Nf6  is that it puts some pressure on the e4-pawn. White has many different options, the most popular being  11.Qf3  ,  11.Bc4  ,  11.Be2  and  11.Qe2  .   The main theoretical move is  10...Ne5  when both  11.Nf5  and  11.f3  are very critical. }
11. Qf3
{ The critical and most played move. The idea is that now  11...Nc6?  is bad in view of  12.Nxc6  bxc6  13.e5! }
11... O-O
{ A very rare line. It leads to great complications, but I think Black is fine. Another good thing about this move is that it is new and White must also be very precise.   The main theoretical continuation is  11...Qb6  12.O-O-O  Nc6  13.Nxc6  Qxc6  . }
12. O-O-O { I see no good alternative to this move. } 12... Nc6 13. Nxc6
{ 13.Nb3  Qb6  is not dangerous at all. } 13... bxc6 14. e5
{ The most natural and logical way to play after 11... O-O. } 14... Nd5
{ This looks very similar to some lines in the Dragon. Here White has the choice of exchanging on d5 and then on d6, or playing Bc4 first. }
15. Nxd5
{ Of course bad is  15.exd6?  in view of  15...Nxc3  16.bxc3  Qa5  when White's king is under a serious attack. }
15... cxd5 16. h4 g4 17. Qxd5 Rb8
{ We've arrived at the critical position for the whole 10... Nf6 line. White has a couple of interesting ideas in this position. }
18. Qe4 { The most critical line. } 18... Qb6 { Provoking b3. } 19. Bd3
{ A very logical move. White is threatening with the mate in one.   19.Qd4  leads to a draw after  19...Qa5  20.Qd5  Qb6=  when White must repeat the moves. }
19... Qxb2+ 20. Kd2 f5 { The only defense. } 21. exf6 Qxf6 22. Qh7+ Kf7 23.
Rhe1 Rb4 { The best move! Black has very serious counterchances. } *

