{ A very rare move in this position, but in my opinion this is the central point of this line! The other moves which have been played are  9...Bb7  ,  9...Nbd7  and  9...b4  . In this relatively new position, White has many different plans. The good news for Black is that he can use the same moves in almost all lines. }
10. a3
{ 10.Kb1  Bb7  and sooner or later, White will play a3, transposing to the 10.a3 line. }
10... Bb7 { The next black moves are very standard, like ...Rc8 and ...Ne5. }
11. Kb1
{ A very standard move in all Sicilians where White castles on the queenside. }
11... Rc8 12. Be2 Be7 { Black just develops his pieces. } 13. h4
{ Sometimes White goes for this move. The idea is to fix the kingside structure.   13.h3  will always be met by  13...h4!  , nicely fixing the kingside. }
13... Ne5 { White will never be allowed to play g4. } 14. Bg5 O-O 15. Rh3
{ The only constructive plan for White. } 15... Re8
{ Black needs to defend calmly. } 16. Rg3
{ This looks scary, but White has no real threats. Now almost every move is good. }
16... Ba8
{ A decent waiting move. In some lines, Black is able to use the b-file. } 17.
f4
{ This is the most concrete way for White to continue.   After  17.Bh6  Bf8  Black defends everything. }
17... Rxc3 { A very standard shot in this kind of positions. } 18. Qxc3 Nxe4
{ The logical follow-up to the sacrifice just played. } 19. Qe1 Nxg3 20. Qxg3
Nc4 21. Bxh5 Qd7
{ The position remains very double-edged, although I prefer Black here. } *

