[White "16) 6.h3 "]
[Black "6.h3 with 7.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3
{ 6.h3  is one of the most popular systems against the Najdorf nowadays. The main idea is to push g4 as soon as possible. }
6... Nc6
{ This is not the most popular response from Black. The main moves are  6...e5  and  6...e6  .  6...g6  is also an option, very similar to the move I'm offering.I decided to suggest  6...Nc6  because I think it leads to very playable positions and is also a bit rare compared to the other moves just mentioned, where the theory is huge. The main idea is to play with ...g6 and ...Bg7 next, but as we will see, against some moves Black will play with ...e5 instead. }
7. Be3 { After  7.g4  this is the second most critical move. } 7... e5
{ Now Black must play with ...e5! Play is very similar to one of the most popular systems against the Najdorf: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  e5  .  The difference is that the moves h3 and ...Nc6 are included. }
8. Nxc6
{ This is very possible. It's definitely the most positional way to continue for White. }
8... bxc6 9. Bc4 { Another standard move. } 9... Be6
{ It is good to exchange this bishop on c4. } 10. Qe2 d5
{ Black must create some threats. } 11. O-O-O Qa5
{ Moving away from the pin. The next move will be ...Bb4. } *

