[Round "?"]
[White "17) 6.Be2 e5 7.Nf3 and Nf5"]
[Black "6.Be2 e5 7.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2
{ One of the most popular systems against the Najdorf, considered to be the most positional approach.  Many great players have had this move as their main weapon against the Najdorf. }
6... e5
{ The main move.  6...e6  would lead to Scheveningen type of positions.  6...e5  is the most popular move these days, and almost all top players prefer it. }
7. Nf3
{ Since Magnus Carlsen played it, this move has become very popular in recent years.  The main idea is to play Bg5-Bxf6 with the intention of taking control of the d5-square. }
7... Be7 { The main move. } 8. Bg5 Nbd7
{ The most complicated move. The idea is to protect the knight on f6, and in case of Bxf6 to recapture with the other knight.  Usually ...Nbd7 is associated with the plan of playing ...b6 and ...Bb7, which I think is very passive and leads to a very unpleasant positional advantage for White. As we will see, I prefer another plan.   More popular lately is  8...Be6  . }
9. O-O
{ Another possible move. Is it very similar to 9. a4, but gives Black a couple of extra options. }
9... h6 { It is almost always good to include this move. } 10. Bh4
{ I prefer Black in this line. } 10... g5 11. Bg3 Nc5
{ The bishop on g3 is completely out of the game. } 12. Nd2 Be6
{ The threat of ...h5 looks quite unpleasant for White. } *

