7... Be7 { The main move. } 8. Bg5 Nbd7
{ The most complicated move. The idea is to protect the knight on f6, and in case of Bxf6 to recapture with the other knight.  Usually ...Nbd7 is associated with the plan of playing ...b6 and ...Bb7, which I think is very passive and leads to a very unpleasant positional advantage for White. As we will see, I prefer another plan.   More popular lately is  8...Be6  . }
9. a4
{ The most popular move, preventing ...b5.   9.Nd2?!  This plan does not work well, the point is that after  9...b5  10.a4  b4  White cannot play  11.Nd5?  because  11...Nxd5  wins a piece. }
9... h6 { The easiest way to achieve an equal game. } 10. Be3 Ng4
{ Very important! Now White must go back with the bishop. } 11. Bc1
{ 11.Bd2  The bishop on d2 is even worse than on c1 because the Nd2 plan is no longer available.  11...Ngf6  White probably should repeat the moves with  12.Be3  Ng4  here. }
11... Ngf6 12. O-O
{ Of course in case of  12.Be3  Black will just repeat the moves with  12...Ng4=  . }
12... Nc5 { This knight belongs to this square. } 13. Nd2 Be6 14. b3
{ The only reasonable plan. } 14... O-O 15. Bb2 Qc7
{ The most ambitious continuation. Black is keeping all the pieces on the board. }
16. Re1 Qc6 17. Bf1 { After  17.Bf3  Black will continue with  17...b5  . }
17... Rad8 18. a5 Rfe8
{ All of Black's pieces are very well placed. In some lines, Black can even think about the ...d6-d5 push. }
*

