[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2
{ One of the most popular systems against the Najdorf, considered to be the most positional approach.  Many great players have had this move as their main weapon against the Najdorf. }
6... e5
{ The main move.  6...e6  would lead to Scheveningen type of positions.  6...e5  is the most popular move these days, and almost all top players prefer it. }
7. Nb3 Be7
{ Practice has shown that this is the best move order. If Black starts with  7...Be6  , then White can play  8.f4  with the idea of ​​disturbing the bishop with f4-f5. }
8. Bg5 Be6
{ This is an important move that forces White to capture on f6, as otherwise ...Nbd7 will be played and Black can retake on f6 with the knight. }
9. Bxf6 { White has to take before Black can play ...Nbd7. } 9... Bxf6 10. Bg4
{ This has been played by Vladimir Kramnik. Certainly this plan is not dangerous for Black at all. }
10... O-O 11. O-O Be7 { The simplest, preparing ...Nd7. } 12. Bxe6
{ It is maybe a little strange to exchange the bishops so soon.   12.Nd5  is an option, but Black can simply reply with  12...Bg5  with ...Nd7 coming on the next move. }
12... fxe6 13. Qg4 Rf6
{ I would already prefer to play with Black here. Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2753@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
*

