13. c3 Bxd5 { Now Black should exchange on d5. } 14. Qxd5 Qb6
{ I really like this move, as the queen blocks the plan Nd2-c4. } 15. Qd3 Nf6
16. O-O O-O 17. Bf3 g6
{ The plan of ...g6 followed by ...h5-h4 and ...Bg7 is always useful in this type of position. }
18. g3 h5 19. h4 { Preventing ...h4. } 19... Rfd8 20. Rd2 Bf8
{ Also an important idea. The position is very equal. } 21. Rfd1 Bh6 22. Rc2
Kg7
{ I don't see any useful plan for White. The knight on b3 is far from the d5-square. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.Bg5"]
[Black "6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.Bg5 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2
{ One of the most popular systems against the Najdorf, considered to be the most positional approach.  Many great players have had this move as their main weapon against the Najdorf. }
6... e5
{ The main move.  6...e6  would lead to Scheveningen type of positions.  6...e5  is the most popular move these days, and almost all top players prefer it. }
7. Nb3 Be7
{ Practice has shown that this is the best move order. If Black starts with  7...Be6  , then White can play  8.f4  with the idea of ​​disturbing the bishop with f4-f5. }
8. Bg5 Be6
{ This is an important move that forces White to capture on f6, as otherwise ...Nbd7 will be played and Black can retake on f6 with the knight. }
9. Bxf6 { White has to take before Black can play ...Nbd7. } 9... Bxf6 10. Qd3
{ The main idea for White is to play with Qd3 and O-O-O. Clearly, this is the most ambitious plan. In the future White's plan is to push the kingside pawns with g3-f4. }
10... Be7
{ The most flexible continuation. The main alternatives are  10...O-O  and  10...Nc6  . }
11. O-O-O Nd7 12. g3
{ This is less popular, but certainly has its reasons. White wants to start pushing pawns immediately on the kingside. }
12... b5 13. f4 Rc8
{ A very typical 'Najdorf move'. The rook in many positions belongs to the c-file. }
14. Kb1 { This does not change much. } 14... O-O 15. Nd5
{ Black is always exchanging that knight in these lines. } 15... Bxd5 16. Qxd5
Qc7 { Black has excellent play. } 17. c3 Nf6 18. Qd3 Rb8
{ The rook has finished its work on the c-file and is ready to begin a new job. }
*

