{ Now it is clear that after  9.O-O  O-O  we transpose to 8. O-O - see the next chapter. Here White has some other options instead of castling. }
9. Nd5
{ One of the most popular lines lately. Definitely this is very critical for the whole 6. Be2 e5 variation. }
9... Nbd7
{ Defending the b6-square and developing a piece. All the other moves are simply worse. }
10. Qd3
{ 10.Nxe7?!  is not a good idea. After  10...Qxe7  11.Bf3  O-O  12.O-O  Rac8  13.Qd2  Rfd8  Black has an excellent position. }
10... O-O 11. c4 b5 { Black is ready for this breakthrough. } 12. Nd2
{ The most solid option. } 12... Nc5
{ The most logical way to play. This practically forces the exchange on c5. }
13. Bxc5
{ 13.Qc2?!  is just not good. After  13...Rc8  Only White can be worse. } 13...
dxc5 14. b3
{ The idea of ​​this move is simple. White defends the c4-pawn, and is ready to take with the c-pawn also after a possible exchange on d5, thus not allowing Black to play ...c4 afterwards. }
14... Bxd5 { Clearly the most logical way to take on d5. } 15. exd5
{ Not a good idea. } 15... e4
{ A strong pawn sacrifice after which Black will be able to create counterplay on the dark squares. }
16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Qa5+
{ White's king will now be forced to remain in the centre. } 18. Kf1 Bf6
{ White should be careful not to end up clearly worse. } *

