{ Practice has shown that this is the best move order. If Black starts with  7...Be6  , then White can play  8.f4  with the idea of ​​disturbing the bishop with f4-f5. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ A very popular move. The point is to play Bf3, Be3 and a4 next with, the idea to establish more control over the d5-square. }
9... Be6 10. Bf3 Qc7
{ I very much like this move order. The point is to keep the knight flexible on b8 a bit longer. In some cases Black can play ...Nc6 instead of ...Nbd7.   The most popular move is  10...Nbd7  . }
11. a4 Rc8 { Still keeping the knight on b8. } 12. Be3 Nbd7 13. a5 h6
{ The most popular move. The move ...h6 is always good to include. } 14. h3
{ The critical position of the 9. Re1 line. I think Black has a lot of interesting options now. }
14... Bd8
{ A new move. I want to suggest it because it is new, but it's very similar to the main move  14...Rab8  .  The idea is still to look for the ...b5 idea.   The main alternatives are  14...Rab8  ,  14...b5  and  14...Qc6  . }
15. Qd2 b5 16. axb6 Nxb6 17. Na5
{ The only way to properly protect the c4-square. } 17... Rab8
{ The chances are equal. Black is preparing ...Nc4. } *

