[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2
{ One of the most popular systems against the Najdorf, considered to be the most positional approach.  Many great players had this move as their main weapon against the Najdorf. }
6... e5
{ The main move.  6...e6  would lead to Scheveningen type of positions.  6...e5  is the most popular move these days, and almost all top players prefer it. }
7. Nb3 Be7
{ Practice has shown that this is the best move order. If Black starts with  7...Be6  , then White can play  8.f4  with the idea of ​​disturbing the bishop with f4-f5. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Qd3
{ This is one of the more popular lines lately. It is quite flexible, as in some lines the bishop can go to d2 instead of e3. }
9... Be6 { The most logical response. } 10. Bd2
{ The main idea behind Qd3. This is a very flexible move; White waits for  10...Nbd7  and only then will play  11.Nd5  .   10.f4  is harmless. After  10...b5  11.Nd5  Nbd7  Black is doing very well.   10.Be3  transposes to the line 9. Be3 Be6 10. Qd3. }
10... Nc6
{ The most popular move. Black intends to use the unstable position of White's queen. }
11. Nd5
{ 11.a3  is not very ambitious.  11...d5  is the easiest way to equalize: after  12.exd5  Nxd5  13.Nxd5  Qxd5  14.Qxd5  Bxd5  15.Be3  Rac8=  the endgame is very equal. }
11... Bxd5
{ The best way to equalize. This has been played by the top Grandmaster Anish Giri. }
12. exd5 e4 { The point! Black does not want to go back to b8. } 13. Qe3 Nxd5
14. Qxe4 Nf6
{ Black has completely changed the nature of the position. White has the bishop pair, but we will see that Black has very good piece play. }
15. Qd3 { The first alternative to the main try  15.Qf5  . } 15... Ne5 16. Qf5
Qc7 { Black will play ...g6 and ...d5 next. } 17. c3 g6 18. Qc2 d5 19. Rad1
Rfe8 { Black's pieces are very active. } *

