{ The main move.  6...e6  would lead to Scheveningen type of positions.  6...e5  is the most popular move these days, and almost all top players prefer it. }
7. Nb3 Be7
{ Practice has shown that this is the best move order. If Black starts with  7...Be6  , then White can play  8.f4  with the idea of ​​disturbing the bishop with f4-f5. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Be3
{ 9.Bf3  most likely will transpose to 9. Re1.  After  9...Be6  sooner or later White will play the moves a2-a4 and Rf1-e1, thus transposing to the 9.Re1 line. }
9... Be6 10. Qd2 { This is the old main line. } 10... Nbd7 11. a4 Nb6
{ The easiest way to equalize. } 12. a5 Nc4 13. Bxc4 Bxc4 14. Rfd1 Rc8
{ The rook obviously belongs here. } 15. Nc1 { The critical line. } 15... d5
{ Equalizes immediately. } 16. Bb6 Qe8 17. Nxd5
{ The main alternative to  17.exd5  . } 17... Nxe4 18. Qe1 f5
{ The most ambitious way of playing. } 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. b3 Bf7 21. c4 Rfe8
{ Black is at least not worse. } *

