[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) 6.Bc4 Various Seventh Moves"]
[Black "6.Bc4 with 7.O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4
{ This was Robert James Fisher's favorite weapon. It is rarely seen these days at the highest level, but it remains a very dangerous move and Black must know exactly what to do. }
6... e6
{ At this point White has many different plans. The most popular plan is to put the bishop on b3 and then to start active actions with f4 or Qf3. Another popular plan is to play either 7. a3 or 7. a4, trying to place the bishop on a2. }
7. O-O
{ Provoking Black into playing  7...b5  which would transpose to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bc4  e6  7.Bb3  b5  8.O-O  . }
7... Be7 { I don't like to transpose to the aforementioned line. } 8. Bb3
{ There are many good replies for Black here. } 8... O-O
{ I see nothing wrong with this move order. } 9. Qf3 Nbd7
{ The most flexible move. The knight goes to c5 or e5. } 10. Qg3 Nc5
{ Putting pressure on e4. } 11. Bh6 Ne8
{ A standard defensive move in this line. } 12. Be3 Kh8 13. Rad1 Qc7
{ The bishop on b3 is out of the game. In the long term this can be a problem for White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) 6.Bc4 Various Seventh Moves"]
[Black "6.Bc4 with 7.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4
{ This was Robert James Fisher's favorite weapon. It is rarely seen these days at the highest level, but it remains a very dangerous move and Black must know exactly what to do. }
6... e6
{ At this point White has many different plans. The most popular plan is to put the bishop on b3 and then to start active actions with f4 or Qf3. Another popular plan is to play either 7. a3 or 7. a4, trying to place the bishop on a2. }
7. a3
{ Not a very ambitous continuation in my opinion. The point is to place the bishop on a2. Usually this line is not very dangerous for Black. }
7... Be7 { The best move order! The key is to postpone b7-b5 here. } 8. Ba2
{ 8.O-O  b5  9.Ba2  O-O  transposes to 8. Ba2. } 8... O-O 9. O-O b5
{ The bishop belongs on b7. This way Black gets a fantastic position. } 10. f4
Bb7 11. f5 e5
{ This structure in general is very good for Black. Normally the plan is to play ...Nbd7, ...Rc8 and to look for the typical sacrifice ...Rxc3. }
12. Nde2 Nbd7 13. Ng3
{ This position arose in the game Olafsson,F-Fischer,R Bled/ Zagreb/Belgrade 1959. }
13... a5
{ An improvement on the game's move, with which Black could have taken the advantage. }
*

