1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4
{ This was Robert James Fisher's favorite weapon. It is rarely seen these days at the highest level, but it remains a very dangerous move and Black must know exactly what to do. }
6... e6
{ At this point White has many different plans. The most popular plan is to put the bishop on b3 and then to start active actions with f4 or Qf3. Another popular plan is to play either 7. a3 or 7. a4, trying to place the bishop on a2. }
7. Be3
{ This move has been popular lately. The idea is to provoke b7-b5 and to avoid the lines with ...Nbd7. }
7... b5 { I believe Black must start with this move. } 8. Bb3 Be7
{ The most accurate move order. The point is to still keep the pawn on e6 protected. Also, in some lines the bishop can go to d7. }
9. a3 { Probably the best move order. White is preventing ...b4. } 9... O-O 10.
f3 Bb7 11. Qe2 Nc6 { The move I like the most. } 12. O-O-O b4
{ My improvement! I think it is very interesting to play this way. The most popular move at the highest level is  12...Na5  . }
13. Nxc6 { To take the pawn seems very logical. } 13... Bxc6 14. axb4 Qb8 15.
Bd2 { A worse continuation compared to  15.Rd4  . } 15... Rc8
{ Black gets a fantastic attack here. } 16. g4 a5
{ The position is becoming extremely dangerous for White. } 17. b5 a4 18. Bc4
Be8 19. g5 Nd7 { I believe Black is better. } *

