1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4
{ This was Robert James Fisher's favorite weapon. It is rarely seen these days at the highest level, but it remains a very dangerous move and Black must know exactly what to do. }
6... e6
{ At this point White has many different plans. The most popular plan is to put the bishop on b3 and then to start active actions with f4 or Qf3. Another popular plan is to play either 7. a3 or 7. a4, trying to place the bishop on a2. }
7. f4 { Not the smartest move order. } 7... b5 { Still the best move. } 8. Bb3
Bb7 9. Be3
{ In case of  9.O-O  Nbd7  White has nothing better than  10.Be3  which will transpose back to 9. Be3. }
9... Nbd7 { The easiest way to deal with 9. Be3. } 10. O-O h5
{ The suggestion of the engines. This is a very original way of playing, not only threatening ...Ng4 but also in many lines preventing the move Qd1-h5.   Another very logical continuation is  10...Rc8  . }
11. Qe2
{ Now after  11.h3  Black can already take the pawn with  11...b4  12.Na4  Nxe4  And Black is better, as the g3-square is weak. }
11... Nc5 { Putting more pressure on e4. } 12. Rad1 Qc7 13. f5
{ White already has no choice. } 13... e5
{ The standard reaction after f4-f5. } 14. Nf3 Nxb3 15. cxb3 Bxe4
{ The best way to capture on e4. } 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Bd4 Nf6
{ White does not have enough compensation for the pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
