[Black "6.g3 with 7.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3
{ This move is usually played by positional players. White wants to fianchetto his bishop and play a slow positional game. }
6... e5
{ Against the 6.g3 system, this is definitely the best option. The logic behind the move is clear, as the bishop on g2 will be blocked for a while. }
7. Nf3
{ A rare move. The main goal is to try to transfer the knight to e3 via h4-g2. }
7... Be7 { The simplest response. Black just wants to develop his pieces. } 8.
Bg2 { This move is possible, but it does not seem very ambitious. } 8... O-O 9.
a4 { The other option, simply preventing ...b5. } 9... Nc6
{ In so many lines, when White starts with a2-a4, Black plays ...Nc6 with the main point to eventually jump to b4. }
10. O-O Be6 { Black just plays the most logical moves. } 11. Nh4
{ Aiming for Nf5 or Nd5.  11.Ng5  leads nowhere after  11...Bd7  . } 11... Nd4
{ The knight looks very good here. } 12. Re1
{ The point is after  12.Be3  to continue with  12...Ng4!  Attacking the knight on h4 is very unpleasant for White. }
12... g6 { Stopping Nf5. } 13. Nd5 { Black is doing well in this line. } 13...
Nxd5 14. exd5 Bd7 { For the moment the threat is ...Bxh4. } 15. Nf3
{ 15.c3  Bxh4  is fine for Black. } 15... Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 f5
{ Black has an excellent position. The next moves are ...Bf6 and ...e4. } *

