1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3
{ This move is usually played by positional players. White wants to fianchetto his bishop and play a slow positional game. }
6... e5
{ Against the 6.g3 system, this is definitely the best option. The logic behind the move is clear, as the bishop on g2 will be blocked for a while. }
7. Nde2
{ The most played and definitely the most critical move. In many lines, White can play Nec3 after putting the c3-knight on d5 or White can even think of h3-g4 and Ng3. }
7... Be7
{ I prefer to develop and castle for now. The alternatives are  7...b5  and  7...Nbd7  . }
8. Bg2 O-O { The other option is  8...b5  . } 9. O-O b5
{ The main move.  9...Be6  is the other line, but theory has shown that Black is slightly worse after  10.a4  Nbd7  11.h3  . }
10. Nd5 Nbd7 11. Nec3
{ The main move. White keeps control over the d5-square.   11.Nxe7+  Qxe7  Black has an easy game here.  12.Nc3  Bb7  13.a3  Rac8  with an equal game. }
11... Nxd5
{ I believe this is the easiest way to equalize. However, more popular are  11...Bb7  and  11...Nb6  . }
12. Qxd5 { This looks harmless. } 12... Nb6 13. Qd3 Be6
{ Black might even get the better position already. } *

