[White "24) 6.Bd3"]
[Black "6.Bd3 with 7.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bd3
{ A very old system that has become very popular at a high level in recent years. Top grandmaster Sergei Karjakin has played it many times. The main point of the move is to develop the bishop and keep the e2-square available for the d4-knight. The main theoretical continuation here is  6...e5  7.Nde2  . }
6... g6
{ This is less popular than the aforementioned main line  6...e5  7.Nde2  .  The bishop on d3 is not the best placed piece against a Dragon setup, so the move 6...g6 makes a lot of sense here. }
7. Be3
{ This contains the same idea as the main move  7.f3  - White prepares Qd2 and long castling. }
7... Ng4
{ This is the main difference between 7. f3 and 7. Be3. This move is very disturbing for White. }
8. Bg5 Bg7 9. Be2 { The only reasonable move. } 9... h6
{ Of course Black will not go back. } 10. Bc1
{ In case of  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  h5  we actually transpose to one of the most popular lines in the 6.Be3 Ng4 variation - see chapter 10. }
10... Qb6 { The main point of Black's idea. } 11. Bxg4
{ White has no other move. } 11... Bxg4 12. Qxg4 Bxd4
{ It looks risky to allow Qc8+, but Black is doing fine. } 13. Nd5
{ Another possible move. } 13... Qc6 { The simplest reply. } 14. c3 Bg7 15. O-O
Nd7 { Black has no problems at all. } *

