1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bd3
{ A very old system that has become very popular at a high level in recent years. Top grandmaster Sergei Karjakin has played it many times. The main point of the move is to develop the bishop and keep the e2-square available for the d4-knight. The main theoretical continuation here is  6...e5  7.Nde2  . }
6... g6
{ This is less popular than the aforementioned main line  6...e5  7.Nde2  .  The bishop on d3 is not the best placed piece against a Dragon setup, so the move 6...g6 makes a lot of sense here. }
7. f3
{ I believe this is the most challenging plan for Black. White wants to castle long after Be3-Qd2. }
7... Qb6
{ A very rare idea. The point is to confuse White's pieces a little.   The most common way to play is  7...Bg7  8.Be3  Nbd7  . }
8. a3
{ White wants to continue with Be3. The knight is untouchable at the moment. }
8... Nc6 { Of course not  8...Qxd4?  in view of  9.Bb5+  . } 9. Be3
{ The whole idea of 8.a3. Black still can't take the knight because of the possible check on b5, or the b2-pawn in view of Na4. }
9... e5
{ The only constructive idea. Eventually, Black will remove this knight from the center. }
10. Nf5
{ Extremely dangerous for White is  10.Bg5  exd4  11.Bxf6  dxc3  12.Bxh8  cxb2  13.Rb1  Ne5!  when Black has serious attacking chances. }
10... Qd8 11. Ng3
{ In case of  11.Nh6  Black equalizes with  11...d5!  provoking the exchange of some pieces.  12.exd5  Nxd5  13.Nxd5  Qxd5  14.Be4  Qxd1+  15.Rxd1  Be6=  with an equal endgame. }
11... Bg7 12. O-O { The normal way to finish the development. } 12... Be6 13.
Qd2 O-O 14. Rad1 Rc8
{ The knight on g3 is placed a little awkwardly. The chances are equal. An interesting idea here can be ...Ne7 with the idea to push d6-d5. }
