1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a3
{ A rare line played a lot by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen. This is a waiting move. The main idea is after  6...e5  7.Nf5  d5  to play  8.Bg5  ,  and in many lines the pawn on a3 protects against the possible check on b4. }
6... e5 { I think this is the best reaction to 6. a3. } 7. Nf3
{ This line is quite similar to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.a4  e5  7.Nf3  . }
7... Be7 8. Bc4
{ The only reasonable plan for White is to take control over the d5-square. }
8... Be6 { It is normal to meet Bc4 with ...Be6. } 9. Ba2 Nbd7
{ I prefer to bring the rook to c8 first and only then castle. } 10. Bg5 Rc8
11. O-O O-O
{ Black is doing very well. Of course White's position is also solid, but his plan is not very clear. }
12. Re1
{ This position arose in the game: Villanueva,M @@StartBracket@@2478@@EndBracket@@-Dominguez Perez,L  @@StartBracket@@2758@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
12... h6
{ An improvement over the mentioned game. Black is disturbing White's bishop. }
13. Bxf6 Nxf6 { Black's play is easier. } *

