[Black "6.a3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a3
{ A rare line played a lot by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen. This is a waiting move. The main idea is after  6...e5  7.Nf5  d5  to play  8.Bg5  ,  and in many lines the pawn on a3 protects against the possible check on b4. }
6... e5 { I think this is the best reaction to 6. a3. } 7. Nf5
{ The main idea of White's previous move. The alternatives are less ambitious. For example,  7.Nb3  is a possible move, but not very well connected to 6. a3. Black will simply develop with  7...Be6  . The move 6. a3 here is just a lost of time. }
7... d5
{ Worse is  7...Bxf5?!  8.exf5  d5  bacause of  9.Bg5  d4  10.Ne4  The point of 6. a3. Now Black doesn't have the move ...Bb4+. }
8. Bg5 d4 9. Bxf6 gxf6
{ The most ambitious continuation. The main point is that Nd5 is not possible because the knight on f5 is hanging.   The other way to play is  9...Qxf6  10.Nd5  Qc6  . }
10. Ne2
{ Magnus Carlsen's idea which he employed blitz games. He played it against me in an online tournament on Chess24. }
10... Qa5+ { The easiest way to refute his idea. } 11. Qd2
{ The endgame is just better for Black.   After  11.b4  Qc7  the move  12.Neg3  is not possible in view of the check on c3. }
11... Qxd2+ { The endgame is very good for Black. } 12. Kxd2 Nd7
{ The knight goes to c5. } 13. Neg3 Nc5 14. Bd3 h5
{ Threatening ...h4, undermining White's f5 knight. } 15. h4 Be6
{ On the next move Black will castle long with the better chances in the endgame. }
*

