1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4
{ This is a very positional line. It should be clear that White intends to play with short castling. }
6... e5 { Here again, I prefer to play with the e7-e5 plan. } 7. Nf3
{ The strongest move. The others create fewer problems for Black. } 7... h6
{ I suggest this move, which is a bit more ambitious than the most commonly played move. Black stops White's idea of Bg5 and prepares ...Be6 after Bc4.   The most common continuation is  7...Be7  . }
8. Bc4
{ The most common reply. This fits in perfectly with White's previous moves. }
8... Be6 { This is Black's main idea. } 9. Bxe6
{ Strategically, this exchange can be very dangerous for White. } 9... fxe6
{ This pawn structure in general is very good for Black. } 10. Nh4
{ White somehow wants to make use of Black's ...h6 move. } 10... Rg8
{ The most accurate. Very bad is  10...Kf7?  because of  11.f4!  exf4  12.e5!  and White is better. }
11. Ng6 Nc6 { Protecting the pawn on e5 and threatening ...Kf7. } 12. O-O Kf7
13. Nxf8 Rxf8 14. Be3 Kg8
{ The central pawns can potentially be very annoying for White. } *

