1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4
{ This is a very positional line. It should be clear that White intends to play with short castling. }
6... e5 { Here again, I prefer to play with the e7-e5 plan. } 7. Nf3
{ The strongest move. The others create fewer problems for Black. } 7... h6
{ I suggest this move, which is a bit more ambitious than the most commonly played move. Black stops White's idea of Bg5 and prepares ...Be6 after Bc4.   The most common continuation is  7...Be7  . }
8. g3
{ This move was tried by Magnus Carlsen and Anish Giri, which is why it definitely needs our attention. }
8... Be7 { Black just develops his pieces. } 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O Nc6
{ This line is very similar to the variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.g3  e5  7.Nf3  ,  but probably a slightly better version for White, because Black has already played the move ...h6. }
11. Re1 Qc7
{ Since White can never play Ng5, this move looks very possible.   11...Rb8  is not the most accurate, and was seen in Giri, A. - Nepomniachtchi, I., Chess24 2021. Anish had to play  12.Nd5  b5  13.axb5  axb5  14.Be3  with a small plus.   Another interesting option is  11...Bd7  . }
12. Nd5 { Black has an excellent position after simply exchanging on d5. }
12... Nxd5 13. exd5 Nb8 { The knight will come into play again via d7. } 14. a5
Bf5 { Just developing. } 15. Be3 Nd7 16. c3 Bg6
{ Black has an excellent position. The next move can be ...f5. } *

