1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4
{ This is a very positional line. It should be clear that White intends to play with short castling. }
6... e5 { Here again, I prefer to play with the e7-e5 plan. } 7. Nf3
{ The strongest move. The others create fewer problems for Black. } 7... h6
{ I suggest this move, which is a bit more ambitious than the most commonly played move. Black stops White's idea of Bg5 and prepares ...Be6 after Bc4.   The most common continuation is  7...Be7  . }
8. Nd2 { A rare but definitely an interesting idea. White threatens Nc4. } 8...
d5
{ I believe this should be the move. The alternative is  8...Be6  9.Nc4  Be7  10.Nd5  Nxd5?!   @@StartBracket@@The point is that after  10...Nxe4  White has  11.Be3  with the initiative.@@EndBracket@@  11.exd5  Bf5  12.a5  Nd7  13.Be2  O-O  14.O-O  Qc7  15.Be3  White was slightly better in the game Tari, A. - Firouzja, A., Stavanger 2021. }
9. exd5 Nxd5
{ White has many options. In all of them Black manages to equalize without much trouble. }
10. Bc4
{ In case of  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  11.Nc4  Qxd1+  12.Kxd1  Nc6=  I think Black does not have serious problems in the endgame. }
10... Nxc3 11. bxc3
{ After  11.Qf3  Black can defend easily with  11...Qf6  when the chances are equal. }
11... Be7 { Black must hurry as his king is still in the center. } 12. Qh5
{ This looks very tempting. } 12... O-O 13. Ne4
{ White has a temporary initiative. } 13... Qc7
{ The best move. Black protects the pawn on e5 and threatens the bishop on c4. }
14. Bd5 a5
{ A very strong novelty. The rook comes into the defense!   Worse is  14...Qd7  . In the game Thavandiran, S. - Vettese, N., Montreal 2017 White had to play  15.c4  Nc6  16.Rb1  Nb4  17.Nf6+  Bxf6  18.Rxb4  with a small edge. }
15. O-O
{ White can make a draw with  15.Bxh6  gxh6  16.Qg6+  Kh8  17.Qxh6+  Kg8=  with a perpetual check. }
15... Ra6 { Intending ...Be6. Black has equal chances. } *

