1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Qe2
{ The worst of the queen moves. } 6... e5
{ Here this definitely is the best move! } 7. Nf5
{ The only idea behind 6. Qe2. The next couple of moves are forced. } 7... d5
{ Using the fact that the knight on f5 is hanging for the moment. } 8. Bg5 d4
9. O-O-O
{ In case of  9.Bxf6  , the recapture  9...gxf6  is the best move. Black prevents White from playing Nd5 and will play ...Be6 next with a clear advantage. }
9... Nc6 { Black keeps it simple. } 10. Qf3 Qa5
{ Clearly the most logical move. } 11. Bxf6 dxc3
{ The game now becomes very concrete, but the complications are in Black's favour. }
12. Bxg7
{ The only move to keep White in the game. Black wins easily after  12.Nxg7+?  Bxg7  13.Bxg7  Rg8  Ramirez Diaz, J. - Merario Alarcon, A. Marbella 2019. }
12... Qxa2 { The best move. Threatening mate in 1. } 13. bxc3
{ 13.Qxc3  loses to  13...Bb4  . } 13... Bxf5 14. Bxf8 Be6
{ I believe White's king is in more danger than the black one. } 15. Bc5 Rg8
{ Threatening ...Bg4. } 16. h3 Rg6
{ It is clear that Black is the one who is pushing. } *

