[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Qd3
{ This queen move became very popular a few years ago. Usually moving the queen this early is not a good idea, but with the new and much more powerful engines anything is possible.   6.Qd3  is actually very interesting. The main point is that now  6...e5  is dubious in view of  7.Nf5  Bxf5  8.exf5  d5  9.Bg5⩲  . }
6... g6
{ To play the Dragon against the queen on d3 seems like a logical idea. Many other moves are quite possible as well. For example:  6...e6  ,  6...Nbd7  or  6...Nc6  . }
7. Bg5
{ The most common move.   7.Be2  Going for the short castle is completely harmless.  7...Bg7  8.O-O  O-O =  Black has many different good plans here. He can start with ...b5 followed by ...Nc6 or ...Nbd7. }
7... Bg7 8. O-O-O
{ 8.f4?!  is not a good move order in view of  8...Nc6  9.O-O-O  Ng4!  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Qd2  Rb8  and Black is slightly better. }
8... h6
{ A rare idea proposed by the engines. More common is  8...O-O  9.f4  Nbd7  . }
9. Bh4 Nc6 { Now this works perfectly. } 10. Nxc6
{ The only idea that makes sense for White. } 10... bxc6 11. e5 Nd5
{ Black is temporarly sacrificing a pawn, but he gets the initiative. } 12.
Nxd5 { The main alternative to  12.exd6  . } 12... cxd5 13. Qxd5
{ After  13.exd6  there's the very good intermediate move  13...Rb8!  with strong counterplay. }
13... Rb8 { Attacking the pawn on b2, thus preventing the move e5xd6. } 14. b3
Be6 15. Qc6+ Bd7
{ The next move will be either short castling or ...Qa5 with a very strong initiative. }
*

