[White "28) 6.h4, 6.Nb3 and 6.Rg1"]
[Black "6.Nb3 e6 7.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Nb3
{ This move is not unusual, in the last few years very strong players have tried it. The idea is to wait for Black's answer and then start pushing g4. }
6... e6
{ I think is the best reply! Now we are entering the Scheveningen type of positions. }
7. a4
{ The positional aproach. Played by the young Russian talent Alekseenko. } 7...
Nc6 { Black is getting ready for play in the center with ...d5. } 8. f4 b6
{ A very typical idea in the Scheveningen type of positions. } 9. g4
{ 9.Be2  Bb7  transposesto 8.Be2. } 9... d5
{ The whole idea. White still lacks development. } 10. Bg2
{ 10.e5  Nd7  Black is doing great in this French-like pawn structure. } 10...
Bb7 { Objectively the best. } 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qh4+
{ An important check. White will not be able to castle anymore. } 13. Kf1 exd5
{ Black is doing great, but the game is very concrete now. } 14. Qxd5 Be7
{ If Black manages to castle White's king will be in big danger. } 15. Qxc6+
{ The only critical try. } 15... Bxc6 16. Bxc6+ Kd8
{ It is important to go this way! } 17. Bxa8 Qxg4
{ The position is very complicated. The whole problem for White is the lack of coordination of his pieces. }
18. Bd2 Qc8 { A double attack! } 19. Be4 Qc4+ 20. Bd3 Qd5 21. Kg1 Qf3
{ Definitely White should be very careful. One idea can be g7-g5! } *

