1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. f3
{ This system has been around for ages. White wants to postpone the development of the queen's knight in order to play c4 first. }
5... e5
{ The most principled continuation. Another decent option is  5...Nc6  6.c4  e6  . }
6. Nb3 d5
{ This move feels so natural. The alternatives are  6...a5  ,  6...Be6  and  6...Nc6  . }
7. Bg5 { The only decent move. } 7... d4
{ Not the most popular, but definitely the most ambitious move. It complicates the game and gives Black an excellent chance to fight for an advantage.   The most popular move is  7...Be6  . }
8. c3 { White must exchange this very strong central pawn on d4. } 8... Nc6
{ White has two main options here,  9.cxd4  and  9.Bb5  . } 9. Bb5
{ It seems logical to put more pressure in the center. } 9... h6
{ To include ...h6-Bh4 is always in Black's favour. } 10. Bh4 Qb6 11. Bxc6+
{ 11.Qd3?!  Nh5!  This was the point in including ...h6. } 11... bxc6 12. cxd4
Ba6 { Looks extremely good for Black. } 13. Bg3
{ The only decent move. Much worse is  13.Bf2?  Rd8  14.N1d2  exd4  and Black was nearly winning in the game Morozevich, A. - Fedoseev, V., Moscow 2016.Black has many interesting options. }
13... Bd6 { The most ambitious move. } 14. Bf2
{ The point is after  14.Nc3  to play  14...Nh5  and the resulting position looks very promising for Black. }
14... Rd8 15. dxe5 Bc5 { An important trick! } 16. Qxd8+
{ 16.Qc2  Bxf2+  17.Qxf2  Rd1+  18.Kxd1  Qxf2  and White can resign. } 16...
Qxd8 17. Nxc5 Nd7 { The bishop on a6 is defended tactically. } 18. Nxa6 Qa5+
{ A simple double attack. } 19. Nc3 Qxa6
{ White still must fight to equalize. } *

