[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This system is known to be very solid. Many players who do not want a big theoretical battle choose this one. Personally, as a Najdorf player, I was never afraid of  4.Qxd4  . }
4... Nc6 { The most natural move. The alternative is  4...Nf6  . } 5. Qe3
{ Recently a very popular move. Honestly, it seems a little awkward for White, but definitely, there are some interesting ideas to investigate. White's plan is to develop with Be2 and O-O, and then to play c4 and Nc3. }
5... g6
{ The most natural way to develop. To play  5...Nf6  is also possible. } 6. Be2
Bg7 { Dubious is  6...Bh6?!  in view of  7.Qc3  . } 7. O-O Nf6
{ White has different move orders here. } 8. c4
{ Not the most accurate move order. } 8... Bg4
{ Black has other options; the most played move in this position is  8...O-O  , followed by  8...Ng4  , but this bishop's sortie looks very interesting. }
9. Nc3 Nd7 { A typical move. Black wants to transfer the knight to c5. } 10. h3
{ A loss of time, Black will still take on f3 sooner or later. } 10... Bxf3 11.
Bxf3 Qb6 { Black has a fantastic version of Maroczy. } 12. Nd5
{ A very instructive line for these type of positions. } 12... Qxe3 13. Bxe3
Rb8
{ A very useful move. It prevents Nc7+, protects the pawn on b7 @@StartBracket@@just in case@@EndBracket@@ and prepares ...e6. }
14. Rab1 e6 15. Nf4
{ Of course after  15.Nc3  the point is  15...Bxc3!  16.bxc3  Ke7  Black is much better. }
15... Ke7 16. Rfd1 a5
{ Black is definitely a little better. The bishop on g7 is a very strong piece. In addition, Black has good control over the dark squares. ...Nc5 and a5-a4 are likely to be Black's next moves. }
*

