{ This system is known to be very solid. Many players who do not want a big theoretical battle choose this one. Personally, as a Najdorf player, I was never afraid of  4.Qxd4  . }
4... Nc6 { The most natural move. The alternative is  4...Nf6  . } 5. Qe3
{ Recently a very popular move. Honestly, it seems a little awkward for White, but definitely, there are some interesting ideas to investigate. White's plan is to develop with Be2 and O-O, and then to play c4 and Nc3. }
5... g6 { The most natural way to develop. To play 5...Nf6 is also possible. }
6. Be2 Bg7 { Dubious is  6...Bh6?!  in view of  7.Qc3  . } 7. O-O Nf6
{ White has different move orders here. } 8. h3
{ Preventing ...Bg4 once and for all. } 8... O-O 9. c4
{ In this move order Black has a very simple plan.   9.Rd1  transposes to  8.Rd1  . }
9... Nd7 10. Nc3 Qb6
{ I think this idea is very nice. The endgame is very good for Black. } 11. Qd2
{ To keep the queens make some sense. White is also threatening Nd5. } 11...
Nc5 12. Nd5 Qd8
{ Black must go back. Also note that the pawn on e4 is unprotected and under attack. }
13. Qc2 f5 { A very typical idea in this pawn structure. } 14. exf5 Bxf5
{ Black is doing great. } *

