1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4
{ This system is known to be very solid. Many players who do not want a big theoretical battle choose this one. Personally, as a Najdorf player, I was never afraid of  4.Qxd4  . }
4... Nc6 { The most natural move. The alternative is  4...Nf6  . } 5. Qe3
{ Recently a very popular move. Honestly, it seems a little awkward for White, but definitely, there are some interesting ideas to investigate. White's plan is to develop with Be2 and O-O, and then to play c4 and Nc3. }
5... g6 { The most natural way to develop. To play 5...Nf6 is also possible. }
6. Be2 Bg7 { Dubious is  6...Bh6?!  in view of  7.Qc3  . } 7. O-O Nf6
{ White has different move orders here. } 8. Rd1 O-O
{ Of course not  8...Bg4?  in view of  9.e5! } 9. h3
{ Delaying c4 makes sense. In some lines, White can even play Nc3 right away. }
9... Be6
{ It is considered the best move. I like it, although I believe that Black has some other good options. }
10. Nc3
{ It looks a little artificial. This is the favourite line of A. Demchenko; also Magnus Carlsen played it a couple of times.   10.Ng5  This is harmless, Black can simply go back  10...Bd7  with an excellent game. }
10... Rc8
{ The most natural move. The endgame after  10...Qb6  11.Qxb6  axb6  12.a3  is still playable for Black, although it is a bit better for White.  12...Rfc8  13.Rb1  White can hope to have a small plus, but I still believe the position should be closer to equal. }
