{ This system is known to be very solid. Many players who do not want a big theoretical battle choose this one. Personally, as a Najdorf player, I was never afraid of  4.Qxd4  . }
4... Nc6 { The most natural move. The alternative is  4...Nf6  . } 5. Bb5
{ The main idea behind 4.Qxd4. Normally White wants, after  5...Bd7  ,  to exchange on c6 and then to play either c4-Nc3 or Nc3 immediately and then Bg5 followed by O-O-O. }
5... a6
{ A rare move compared to the most popular continuation,  5...Bd7  , which is also fine. I prefer  5...a6  because is a bit more ambitious and gives Black more fighting chances. }
6. Bxc6+ bxc6
{ The bishop pair and the potentially good pawns in the center give Black hope in the long term. Of course, in the short term, Black should be careful because of the lack of development.White has many different moves, but two basic concepts. One concept is to try to attack the weak black pawns immediately, and the other is to just castle and continue with c4-Nc3. }
