1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+
{ The most popular way to deviate from the Open Sicilian. This system is quite unpleasant for Black because it is very solid and it is quite difficult to gain any activity. Nevertheless, Black has several options to have an equal game. }
3... Bd7
{ The most solid approach. Both  3...Bd7  and  3...Nd7  are the most popular move. Lately the move  3...Nc6  is considered to be a little worse for Black. }
4. Bxd7+ { In addition to this move, White has several other alternatives. }
4... Qxd7 5. O-O
{ One of the two main lines, along with  5.c4  , which we will analyze later. }
5... Nf6
{ A very critical position. White has different plans. It looks very logical to play Re1 or Qe2 and to prepare c3-d4. }
6. e5 { There are many games, but it is absolutely harmless. } 6... dxe5 7.
Nxe5 Qc7
{ The most natural continuation, attacking the knight on e5. Also good is 7...Qc8!? }
8. d4 { The only critical line. } 8... cxd4
{ Risky is  8...e6?!  because of  9.Bf4  . } 9. Bf4
{ A very tempting idea. Black should know what to do. After  9.Qxd4  Nc6  Black is just fine.  10.Nxc6  Qxc6  11.Bg5  Ne4  12.Be3  e6=  Black equalizes without much trouble. }
9... Qb6
{ The play is very concrete now, but for the moment Black is a pawn up. } 10.
Nd2 e6 11. Ndc4 Qc5 { The most ambitious. } 12. c3 dxc3 13. bxc3 Be7
{ Black just needs to castle. } 14. Rb1 b5 15. Qf3 Qd5
{ The only move for Black. } 16. Rxb5 Qxf3 17. Nxf3 O-O
{ The endgame is equal, but if somebody can be better that definitely is Black. }
*

