[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bd3
{ Another rare move. The idea is similar to the  3.c3  Nf6  4.Bd3  line. Here the difference is that White wants first to castle and just then to look for c2-c3. }
3... Nc6 4. O-O Nf6 5. Re1 { Black has many different options here. } 5... a6
{ This is the one I like the most. The idea is to stop Bb5 in some lines, and also to prepare b7-b5. }
6. Bf1 e5 { For the moment Black stops d4. } 7. c3
{ White has nothing better than to prepare d4. } 7... Be7 8. h3
{ A prophylactic measure. White needs to lose another tempo before playing d4. }
8... O-O 9. d4 exd4 10. cxd4 d5
{ This central break equalizes the game very easily. } 11. exd5
{ 11.e5  Ne4  The knight on e4 is a very strong piece. } 11... Nxd5 12. dxc5
Bxc5 { Black has no problems at all. The game is completely equal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33) The Alapin"]
[Black "2...e5 3.d4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ The Alapin has always bothered me a lot. It is very difficult for Black to create fighting opportunities. }
2... e5
{ The line that I suggest is extremely rare compared to  2...d5  and  2...Nf6  . I think is nice to have this line in our repertoire, because is less known and objectively Black is fine as well. }
3. d4 { It's harmless. Black equalizes easily. } 3... exd4 4. cxd4
{ 4.Nf3  Nc6  transposesto 3.Nf3. } 4... cxd4 5. Nf3
{ In this move order, Black has an extra chance with his dark-squared bishop. }
5... Bc5 { Quickly mobilizing the minor pieces for counterplay in the center. }
6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O { Black's next move will be ...d5. } 8. Be2 d5
{ With a very easy game for Black. } *

