[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34) 2.Nc3 d6 3.Bb5+ and 3.Nge2"]
[Black "2.Nc3 d6 3.Nge2 with 4.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 { This is the move for Najdorf Players. } 3. Nge2
{ A tricky move order. } 3... Nf6 4. g3 { White wants to postpone d4 for now. }
4... Nc6 5. Bg2 g6 6. d3
{ The most solid approach. The positions that originate from this setup are usually very complex. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O
{ 7.h3  White can postpone castling, but after  7...O-O  8.f4  Rb8  sooner or later White will castle, thus transposing to the main line. }
7... O-O 8. h3 Rb8
{ A very standard move in these types of positions. Black intends to continue with ...b5, gaining space on the queenside. }
9. Be3
{ Another standard maneuver. Here it just turns out to be a loss of time. }
9... b5 10. Qd2 { If  10.a3  then  10...a5  ,  with the idea of ...b4. } 10...
b4 11. Nd1
{ This position arose in the game Vachier Lagrave,M @@StartBracket@@2745@@EndBracket@@-Dominguez Perez,L @@StartBracket@@2754@@EndBracket@@, Beijing 2013, The Week in Chess 1997. }
11... a5
{ I like this approach: Black keeps taking up space on the queenside. } 12. Bh6
{ Exchanging the bishops is not a good idea. } 12... Bxh6 13. Qxh6 Nd4
{ Black is better. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
