[Round "?"]
[White "34) 2.Nc3 d6 3.Bb5+ and 3.Nge2"]
[Black "2.Nc3 d6 3.Nge2 with 4.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 { This is the move for Najdorf Players. } 3. Nge2
{ A tricky move order. } 3... Nf6 4. g3 { White wants to postpone d4 for now. }
4... Nc6 5. Bg2 g6 6. d3
{ The most solid approach. The positions that originate from this setup are usually very complex. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O
{ 7.h3  White can postpone castling, but after  7...O-O  8.f4  Rb8  sooner or later White will castle, thus transposing to the main line. }
7... O-O 8. h3 Rb8
{ A very standard move in these types of positions. Black intends to continue with ...b5, gaining space on the queenside. }
9. f4
{ In this line White plays on the kingside, without preventing Black's ...b5 with a4. }
9... Nd7
{ Preparing ...b5, which cannot be played immediately:  9...b5  in view of  10.e5! }
10. g4 b5 { Black continues with his usual queenside plan. } 11. Ng3 b4 12.
Nce2 Nd4 13. g5 a5 { Black definitely has his chances to take the advantage. }
