1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. a4
{ I remember that during the game I did not know this move. That's why I wasn't sure how to go about it, whether with 7...e6 or 7...g6. }
7... g6 { Not so bad, but is a little passive.   The best move is:  7...e6 } 8.
a5
{ Not the most accurate. Better was:  8.Be2  Bg7  9.Qd2  O-O  10.O-O  Nc5  11.f3  with small plus. }
8... Bg7 9. Be2 Nc5
{ The best plan is:  9...b5!  The point is that after:  10.Nc6   Black is fine after:  10.axb6  Bb7=  Qc7  11.Nxe7  Black has  11...Bb7!  12.Ned5  Nxd5  13.exd5  O-O  14.O-O  Rac8=∞  with a very nice counterplay. }
10. Bf3 O-O 11. O-O { Black does not have a clear plan now. } 11... h6 12. Be3
e6 { Very suspicious, but I did not find anything better. } 13. Nb3
{ Very strong is:  13.e5!  dxe5  14.Nc6!  bxc6  15.Bxc5  Nd5  During the game I thought Black has some compensation for the exchange, unfortunately the engines suggest that White is much better after:  16.Na4± }
13... Nxb3 14. cxb3 g5 15. Na4 { Probably better is the simple  15.Qd2± } 15...
Bd7
{ White is still better, but already he needs to find some very precise moves. }
16. Bb6
{ Also not so clear is:  16.Nb6  Rb8  The point is that  17.Qxd6  is not good in view of  17...Bb5  18.Qxd8  Rfxd8=∞   16.Qxd6  Bb5  17.e5  Nd5  Black has fighting chances.   16.e5!  The best move.  16...dxe5  17.Bxb7  Bb5  This position does not look clear from the practical point of view. The engines think that after:  18.Bxa8  Qxa8  19.Nb6!  Qb8  20.Nc4  Nd5  21.Qd2±  White is much better. }
16... Qb8 17. Rc1 Bc6 18. e5 { If  18.Bd4  then  18...Qc7  19.Nb6  Rad8 } 18...
dxe5 19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. Rxc6 e4 { Probably better was  20...Nd5 } 21. Nc3
{ Better is:  21.Qe2 } 21... Rc8 22. Rc4
{ Better was  22.Rxc8+  Qxc8  23.Qd6  Qb7  24.Rd1⩲  with a small plus for White. }
22... Qb7 23. Qe2 Nd7 { Black is already fine. } 24. Nxe4 Rxc4 25. Nd6 Re4
{ A very important nuance! } 26. Qf3 Qc6 27. Nxe4 Rc8
{ Black keeps everything together with this move. } 28. Rd1
{ Maybe better was  28.Be3  f5  29.Nd2  f4  30.Qxc6  Rxc6  31.Ba7  with equality. }
28... Nxb6 29. axb6 Qxb6
{ White already should be careful. To play with Black is definitely easier. }
30. Nd6 Rf8 31. Nc4 Qc7 32. Ra1 Rd8 33. g3
{ Possible was:  33.Rxa6  with the idea after:  33...Qb7  to play  34.Rd6= }
33... Qa7 34. Kg2 Rd5 35. Qe4 h5
{ With every move the position becomes more difficult for White. The bishop is clearly stronger than the knight. }
36. Qe2 Qb7 37. Qe4 Qa7 38. h3 Bd4 39. Rd1 Qc5 40. Rd2 Kg7
{ Just improving all of my pieces. } 41. Rc2 Qb5 42. Rd2 Qc5 43. Rc2 Qe7 44.
Rd2 Qf6 45. Rc2 Ba7 { I had something in mind with this move. } 46. Re2 h4 47.
g4 Bb8 { This was the point. The bishop will be untouchable on f4. } 48. Qf3
{ White did not handle the pressure. He should have kept the queens. The endgame is much more difficult to defend. }
48... Qxf3+ 49. Kxf3 Bf4 50. Kg2 Rb5 { Also good is:  50...Rd3  51.b4  Rb3∓ }
51. Nd2 { The only chance was  51.Re1  Rxb3  52.Ra1 } 51... Kf8
{ More technical was:  51...Bxd2!  52.Rxd2  Rxb3  The endgame is completely winning. White will never exchange the pawn b2 for the pawn a6. }
52. Ne4 a5 53. Nd2 { Very important was:  53.Rc2! } 53... Rb4
{ I still didn't want to exchange on d2. } 54. Kf1 Ke7 55. Kg2 a4
{ I somehow found the way. The game is over. } 56. Nf3 { 56.bxa4  Rxb2-+ }
56... axb3 57. Ne5 Kd6 58. Nd3 Rd4 59. Nxf4 gxf4 60. Kf3 e5 61. g5 Ke6 62. Re4
Rd2 63. Rb4 Kf5 64. Rb5 Rxb2 65. Kg2 Rb1 66. Kf3 b2 67. Kg2 Kg6 68. Kf3 e4+ *

