[Black "Sergey Karjakin - Ivan Cheparinov, European Championship, Porto Carras 2011"]
[Result "*"]

{ Playing against Russia in the Olympics and European team championships was my favorite thing. Many times the not-so-ambitious Bulgarian team managed to beat the powerful Russia. In this match, we did the impossible once again. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ Sergey is known as an expert in the Najdorf with both colours. I was ready for a fight, that was clear. }
6. Be3 { He is choosing the most principled variation. } 6... e6
{ In the period 2005-2012 this was my main weapon. } 7. f3 b5 8. Qd2 Nbd7 9. g4
h6 10. O-O-O b4 11. Nce2 { At that time also popular was:  11.Na4  Ne5 } 11...
Qc7 12. h4 d5 13. Bh3
{ The theory still had to be developed. Later 13. Bf4 become more popular. }
13... Nb6 14. b3 dxe4 15. g5
{ I was very surprised. I thought this is not the most critical.   In my files as the main line I had  15.Bf4  e3! }
15... Nfd5 16. fxe4 Nxe3 17. Qxe3 hxg5 18. hxg5
{ A positional mistake. The engine suggests that only  18.Qxg5  keeps the balance. }
18... g6 { Black is already better. } 19. Kb1 Bg7 20. Rhf1 Qe5
{ The queen and the bishop on g7 are simply deciding the game. White hardly can move. }
21. Qf2 Ra7 { Very simple and strong move. } 22. Ng1 Rc7 23. Ngf3 Qc5 24. Qd2
Qc3
{ Maybe not the best move, but definitely the most technical. In the endgame, nothing can happen. White has no counter-chances at all. }
25. Bg4 Qxd2 26. Rxd2 Ke7 27. Rdf2 Nd7 28. Ne2 Bb7 29. Ne1 Ne5 30. Nd3 Ke8
{ Very simple. } 31. Nxe5 Bxe5 32. Bf3 Rh4 33. Nc1 Bxe4
{ It is time to take some pawns. } 34. Re2 Bxf3 35. Rxe5 Be4 36. Rf2 Bf5 37.
Ra5 Rc6 38. Rg2 Rh3 39. Re5 Rh1 40. Kb2 Rd6 41. Nd3 Bxd3 42. cxd3 Rxd3 43. Re4
a5 44. Re5 Rd5 45. Rxd5 exd5 46. Rd2 Rf1
{ White resigned in view of  47.Rxd5  Rf5-+ } *

