[Result "*"]

{ We are now in the era of online chess. This game was played in the European Online Club Cup. The match was very important for my team. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2
{ Alexei is known for his style, so it was not a suprise that he is choosing this line. }
5... g6 { The main theoretical move.   I suggest  5...Nf6  6.b3  e6 } 6. b3 Bh6
7. f4 Nf6 { Also an option is:  7...f5!? } 8. Bb2 O-O 9. O-O-O a5 10. a4 Nb4
11. Nf3 { 11.Kb1!?  Maybe makes sense. } 11... Bg4 12. Kb1 Rc8
{ Black threatens ...Ne4 and ...Rxc2 in some lines. } 13. Bc4
{ I did not remember my own analysis. } 13... Qb6
{ I had in my files  13...Rxc4!?  14.bxc4  Qc7=∞ } 14. h3
{ Interesting is:  14.Rhf1!? } 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nh5 16. Ne2 Rxc4
{ I thought I had to do it. More solid is:  16...Bg7  . } 17. bxc4 Rc8 18. Qc3
{ Stronger was  18.Qd4  Qxd4  19.Bxd4  Nxf4  20.Nxf4  Bxf4  For me it was not clear why Black is worse here. The engines are giving some advantage. }
18... Bg7 19. Qb3 Bxb2 20. Kxb2 Qc5
{ A solid move.   20...Qf2!  The only move which is giving the advantage. I saw it what I didn't see was  21.Rhe1  Rc6!  The key move! Looks scary for White. }
21. f5 Qe5+ { Better was:  21...Nc6!  22.Rd5  Qf2=∞ } 22. Kb1
{ Stronger was  22.c3!  Na6  23.Rd5  Qf6  24.h4  Nc5  25.Qc2± } 22... Nf6
{ I believe in rapid chess it is easier to play this position with the black pieces. }
23. Nc3 { 23.Rhe1!? } 23... Rc5
{ 23...Qc5!  24.Rhe1  Qxc4  25.Qxc4  Rxc4  26.Kb2  Nd7⩲ } 24. Nb5
{ Better was  24.Rhe1! } 24... Kf8 { I had to move something. } 25. fxg6 hxg6
26. h4 Qe6 27. Rd4 { Not very human is:  27.Na3!? } 27... Rh5 28. c5
{ A stupid human reaction, to exchange queens with material up. Black is already not worse.   Stronger is:  28.Nc3!  Qe5  29.Ne2 }
28... Rxc5 29. Qxe6 fxe6 30. Rd2 Kf7 31. Rg1 Nc6 32. Nd4 Ne5
{ The position is already very difficult for White. } 33. Rf1
{ Better is:  33.f4  Nc4  34.Rdg2   33...Nxe4?  34.Rdg2 } 33... Nc4
{ I completely missed  33...Rc4∓ } 34. Rd3 Rh5 35. Ka2
{ Possible was  35.Rh1  g5  36.Kc1  gxh4  37.Rc3  Nb6  38.Rc7= } 35... Nd7
{ 35...Rxh4  36.Rb1 } 36. Rc3 Ndb6 37. Rb1 Rxh4 38. Nb5
{ Going in the wrong direction.   38.Nb3!  The only way  38...d5  39.Nxa5  Nxa4  40.Rxc4  dxc4  41.Rxb7= }
38... d5 39. Rcb3 Nxa4 40. Nc3 Nxc3+ 41. Rxc3 b6
{ White has no counterplay at all. } 42. Rg1 Rh2 43. Kb1 b5 44. Rd3 b4 45. exd5
exd5 46. Rxd5 Na3+ 47. Kb2 Rxc2+ 48. Kb3 Rc3+ 49. Ka4 Nc4 50. Kb5 b3 51. Rd4
Na3+ 52. Kxa5 b2 53. Rf4+ Kg7 54. Re4 b1=Q 55. Rxb1 Nxb1 *

